{"title_page": "ISO 639-2", "text_new": "{{short description|International standard for three-letter codes identifying languages}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=June 2017}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"25%\" align=\"right\"\n! Find a language\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | Enter an ISO 639-2 code to find the corresponding language article\n|-\n|<inputbox>\ntype=search\nwidth=10\ndefault=ISO 639:\nbuttonlabel=Go\nsearchbuttonlabel=Search\nbreak=no\n</inputbox>\n|}\n\n'''ISO 639-2:1998''', ''Codes for the representation of names of languages \u2014 Part 2: Alpha-3 code'', is the second part of the [[ISO 639]] [[International standard|standard]], which lists [[Language code|code]]s for the representation of the names of [[languages]]. The three-letter codes given for each language in this part of the standard are referred to as \"Alpha-3\" codes. There are 487 entries in the [[list of ISO 639-2 codes]].\n\nThe [[United States|US]] [[Library of Congress]] is the registration authority for ISO 639-2 (referred to as ISO 639-2/RA). As registration authority, the LOC receives and reviews proposed changes; they also have representation on the ISO 639-RA Joint Advisory Committee responsible for maintaining the ISO 639 code tables.\n\n==History and relationship to other ISO 639 standards==\n\nWork was begun on the ISO 639-2 standard in 1989, because the [[ISO 639-1]] standard, which uses only two-letter codes for languages, is not able to accommodate a sufficient number of languages. The ISO 639-2 standard was first released in 1998. \n\nIn practice, ISO 639-2 has largely been superseded by [[ISO 639-3]] (2007), which includes codes for all the individual languages in ISO 639-2 plus many more. It also includes the special and reserved codes, and is designed not to conflict with ISO 639-2. ISO 639-3, however, does not include any of the collective languages in ISO 639-2; most of these are included in [[ISO 639-5]].\n\n==B and T codes==\nWhile most languages are given one code by the standard, twenty of the languages described have two three-letter codes, a \"bibliographic\" code (ISO 639-2/B), which is derived from the English name for the language and was a necessary [[legacy systems|legacy]] feature, and a \"terminological\" code (ISO 639-2/T), which is derived from the native name for the language and resembles the language's two-letter code in ISO 639-1. There were originally 22 B codes; '''scc''' and '''scr''' are now deprecated.\n\nIn general the T codes are favored; [[ISO 639-3]] uses ISO 639-2/T. <!--(wrong, these are based on script names in English, not language codes) However, [[ISO 15924]] derives its codes (for the representation of names of scripts) from ISO 639-2/B when possible.-->\n\n==Scopes and types==\nThe codes in ISO 639-2 have a variety of \"scopes of denotation\", or types of meaning and use, some of which are described in more detail below. \n* Individual languages\n* Macrolanguages (see [[ISO 639 macrolanguage]])\n* [[#Collections of languages|Collections of languages]]\n* Dialects\n* [[#Reserved for local use|Reserved for local use]]\n* [[#Special situations|Special situations]]\n\nFor a definition of macrolanguages and collective languages, see [http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/scope.asp ISO 639-3/RA: Scope of denotation for language identifiers].\n\nIndividual languages are further classified as to type:\n* Living languages\n* Extinct languages\n* Ancient languages\n* Historic languages\n* Constructed languages\n\n{{anchor|Collective language codes}}\n===Collections of languages===\nSome ISO 639-2 codes that are commonly used for languages do not precisely represent a particular language or some related languages (as the above macrolanguages). They are regarded as collective language codes and are excluded from [[ISO 639-3]].\n\nThe collective language codes in ISO 639-2 are listed below.\n\nThe following code is identified as a collective code in ISO 639-2 but is (at present) missing from ISO 639-5:\n*{{samp|him}} [[Himachali languages|Himachali]]\n\nCodes registered for 639-2 that are listed as collective codes in ISO 639-5 (and collective codes by name in ISO 639-2):\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n*{{samp|afa}} [[Afro-Asiatic languages]]\n*{{samp|alg}} [[Algonquian languages]]\n*{{samp|apa}} [[Apache languages]]\n*{{samp|art}} [[artificial languages]]\n*{{samp|ath}} [[Athapascan languages]]\n*{{samp|aus}} [[Australian languages]]\n*{{samp|bad}} [[Banda languages]]\n*{{samp|bai}} [[Bamileke languages]]\n*{{samp|bat}} [[Baltic languages]]\n*{{samp|ber}} [[Berber languages]]\n*{{samp|bih}} [[Bihari languages]]\n*{{samp|bnt}} [[Bantu languages]]\n*{{samp|btk}} [[Batak languages]]\n*{{samp|cai}} [[Central American Indian languages]]\n*{{samp|cau}} [[Caucasian languages]]\n*{{samp|cel}} [[Celtic languages]]\n*{{samp|cmc}} [[Chamic languages]]\n*{{samp|cpe}} creoles and pidgins, English-based\n*{{samp|cpf}} creoles and pidgins, French-based\n*{{samp|cpp}} creoles and pidgins, Portuguese-based\n*{{samp|crp}} [[creole language|creoles]] and [[pidgin]]s\n*{{samp|cus}} [[Cushitic languages]]\n*{{samp|day}} [[Land Dayak languages]]\n*{{samp|dra}} [[Dravidian languages]]\n*{{samp|fiu}} [[Finno-Ugrian languages]]\n*{{samp|gem}} [[Germanic languages]]\n*{{samp|ijo}} [[Ijo languages]]\n*{{samp|inc}} [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indic languages]]\n*{{samp|ine}} [[Indo-European languages]]\n*{{samp|ira}} [[Iranian languages]]\n*{{samp|iro}} [[Iroquoian languages]]\n*{{samp|kar}} [[Karen languages]]\n*{{samp|khi}} [[Khoisan languages]]\n*{{samp|kro}} [[Kru languages]]\n*{{samp|map}} [[Austronesian languages]]\n*{{samp|mkh}} [[Mon\u2013Khmer languages]]\n*{{samp|mno}} [[Manobo languages]]\n*{{samp|mun}} [[Munda languages]]\n*{{samp|myn}} [[Mayan languages]]\n*{{samp|nah}} [[Nahuatl languages]]\n*{{samp|nai}} [[North American Indian languages]]\n*{{samp|nic}} [[Niger\u2013Congo languages|Niger-Kordofanian languages]]\n*{{samp|nub}} [[Nubian languages]]\n*{{samp|oto}} [[Otomian languages]]\n*{{samp|paa}} [[Papuan languages]]\n*{{samp|phi}} [[Philippine languages]]\n*{{samp|pra}} [[Prakrit languages]]\n*{{samp|roa}} [[Romance languages]]\n*{{samp|sai}} [[South American Indian languages]]\n*{{samp|sal}} [[Salishan languages]]\n*{{samp|sem}} [[Semitic languages]]\n*{{samp|sgn}} [[sign language]]s\n*{{samp|sio}} [[Siouan languages]]\n*{{samp|sit}} [[Sino-Tibetan languages]]\n*{{samp|sla}} [[Slavic languages]]\n*{{samp|smi}} [[Sami languages]]\n*{{samp|son}} [[Songhai languages]]\n*{{samp|ssa}} [[Nilo-Saharan languages]]\n*{{samp|tai}} [[Tai languages]]\n*{{samp|tup}} [[Tupi languages]]\n*{{samp|tut}} [[Altaic languages]]\n*{{samp|wak}} [[Wakashan languages]]\n*{{samp|wen}} [[Sorbian languages]]\n*{{samp|ypk}} [[Yupik languages]]\n*{{samp|znd}} [[Zande languages]]\n}}\n\n===Reserved for local use===\nThe interval from '''qaa''' to '''qtz''' is 'reserved for local use' and is not used in ISO 639-2 nor in [[ISO_639-3#Special_codes|ISO 639-3]]. These codes are typically used privately for languages not (yet) in either standard.\n\n===Special situations===\nThere are four generic codes for special situations:\n*'''mis''' is listed as \"uncoded languages\" (originally an abbreviation for \"miscellaneous\")\n*'''mul''' (for multiple languages) is applied when several languages are used and it is not practical to specify all the appropriate language codes\n*'''und''' (for undetermined) is used in situations in which a language or languages must be indicated but the language cannot be identified.\n*'''zxx''' is listed in the code list as \"no linguistic content\", e.g. animal sounds (added 2006-01-11)\nThese four codes are also used in [[ISO_639-3#Special_codes|ISO 639-3]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of ISO 639-2 codes]]\n*[[Language code]]\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.loc.gov/standards/iso639-2/}}\n*[https://www.loc.gov/standards/iso639-2/php/code_changes.php ISO 639-2/RA Change Notice] at the [[Library of Congress]]\n*[https://www.iso.org/standard/4767.html ISO 639-2:1998: Codes for the representation of names of languages\u2014Part 2: Alpha-3 code] at the [[International Organization for Standardization]]\n\n\n{{Footer ISO 639}}\n{{ISO standards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iso 639-2}}\n[[Category:ISO 639]]\n[[Category:1989 introductions]]\n[[Category:Language identifiers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|International standard for three-letter codes identifying languages}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=June 2017}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"25%\" align=\"right\"\n! Find a language\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | Enter an ISO 639-2 code to find the corresponding language article\n|-\n|<inputbox>\ntype=search\nwidth=10\ndefault=ISO 639:\nbuttonlabel=Go\nsearchbuttonlabel=Search\nbreak=no\n</inputbox>\n|}\n\n'''ISO 639-2:1998''', ''Codes for the representation of names of languages \u2014 Part 2: Alpha-3 code'', is the second part of the [[ISO 639]] [[International standard|standard]], which lists [[Language code|code]]s for the representation of the names of [[languages]]. The three-letter codes given for each language in this part of the standard are referred to as \"Alpha-3\" codes. There are 487 entries in the [[list of ISO 639-2 codes]].\n\nThe [[United States|US]] [[Library of Congress]] is the registration authority for ISO 639-2 (referred to as ISO 639-2/RA). As registration authority, the LOC receives and reviews proposed changes; they also have representation on the ISO 639-RA Joint Advisory Committee responsible for maintaining the ISO 639 code tables.\n\n==History and relationship to other ISO 639 standards==\n\nWork was begun on the ISO 639-2 standard in 1989, because the [[ISO 639-1]] standard, which uses only two-letter codes for languages, is not able to accommodate a sufficient number of languages. The ISO 639-2 standard was first released in 1998. \n\nIn practice, ISO 639-2 has largely been superseded by [[ISO 639-3]] (2007), which includes codes for all the individual languages in ISO 639-2 plus many more. It also includes the special and reserved codes, and is designed not to conflict with ISO 639-2. ISO 639-3, however, does not include any of the collective languages in ISO 639-2; most of these are included in [[ISO 639-5]].\n\n==B and T codes==\nWhile most languages are given one code by the standard, twenty of the languages described have two three-letter codes, a \"bibliographic\" code (ISO 639-2/B), which is derived from the English name for the language and was a necessary [[legacy systems|legacy]] feature, and a \"terminological\" code (ISO 639-2/T), which is derived from the native name for the language and resembles the language's two-letter code in ISO 639-1. There were originally 22 B codes; '''scc''' and '''scr''' are now deprecated.\n\nIn general the T codes are favored; [[ISO 639-3]] uses ISO 639-2/T. <!--(wrong, these are based on script names in English, not language codes) However, [[ISO 15924]] derives its codes (for the representation of names of scripts) from ISO 639-2/B when possible.-->\n\n==Scopes and types==\nThe codes in ISO 639-2 have a variety of \"scopes of denotation\", or types of meaning and use, some of which are described in more detail below. \n* Individual languages\n* Macrolanguages (see [[ISO 639 macrolanguage]])\n* [[#Collections of languages|Collections of languages]]\n* Dialects\n* [[#Reserved for local use|Reserved for local use]]\n* [[#Special situations|Special situations]]\n\nFor a definition of macrolanguages and collective languages, see [http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/scope.asp ISO 639-3/RA: Scope of denotation for language identifiers].\n\nIndividual languages are further classified as to type:\n* Living languages\n* Extinct languages\n* Ancient languages\n* Historic languages\n* Constructed languages\n\n{{anchor|Collective language codes}}\n===Collections of languages===\nSome ISO 639-2 codes that are commonly used for languages do not precisely represent a particular language or some related languages (as the above macrolanguages). They are regarded as collective language codes and are excluded from [[ISO 639-3]].\n\nThe collective language codes in ISO 639-2 are listed below.\n\nThe following code is identified as a collective code in ISO 639-2 but is (at present) missing from ISO 639-5:\n*<tt>him</tt> [[Himachali languages|Himachali]]\n\nCodes registered for 639-2 that are listed as collective codes in ISO 639-5 (and collective codes by name in ISO 639-2):\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n*<tt>afa</tt> [[Afro-Asiatic languages]]\n*<tt>alg</tt> [[Algonquian languages]]\n*<tt>apa</tt> [[Apache languages]]\n*<tt>art</tt> [[artificial languages]]\n*<tt>ath</tt> [[Athapascan languages]]\n*<tt>aus</tt> [[Australian languages]]\n*<tt>bad</tt> [[Banda languages]]\n*<tt>bai</tt> [[Bamileke languages]]\n*<tt>bat</tt> [[Baltic languages]]\n*<tt>ber</tt> [[Berber languages]]\n*<tt>bih</tt> [[Bihari languages]]\n*<tt>bnt</tt> [[Bantu languages]]\n*<tt>btk</tt> [[Batak languages]]\n*<tt>cai</tt> [[Central American Indian languages]]\n*<tt>cau</tt> [[Caucasian languages]]\n*<tt>cel</tt> [[Celtic languages]]\n*<tt>cmc</tt> [[Chamic languages]]\n*<tt>cpe</tt> creoles and pidgins, English-based\n*<tt>cpf</tt> creoles and pidgins, French-based\n*<tt>cpp</tt> creoles and pidgins, Portuguese-based\n*<tt>crp</tt> [[creole language|creoles]] and [[pidgin]]s\n*<tt>cus</tt> [[Cushitic languages]]\n*<tt>day</tt> [[Land Dayak languages]]\n*<tt>dra</tt> [[Dravidian languages]]\n*<tt>fiu</tt> [[Finno-Ugrian languages]]\n*<tt>gem</tt> [[Germanic languages]]\n*<tt>ijo</tt> [[Ijo languages]]\n*<tt>inc</tt> [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indic languages]]\n*<tt>ine</tt> [[Indo-European languages]]\n*<tt>ira</tt> [[Iranian languages]]\n*<tt>iro</tt> [[Iroquoian languages]]\n*<tt>kar</tt> [[Karen languages]]\n*<tt>khi</tt> [[Khoisan languages]]\n*<tt>kro</tt> [[Kru languages]]\n*<tt>map</tt> [[Austronesian languages]]\n*<tt>mkh</tt> [[Mon\u2013Khmer languages]]\n*<tt>mno</tt> [[Manobo languages]]\n*<tt>mun</tt> [[Munda languages]]\n*<tt>myn</tt> [[Mayan languages]]\n*<tt>nah</tt> [[Nahuatl languages]]\n*<tt>nai</tt> [[North American Indian languages]]\n*<tt>nic</tt> [[Niger\u2013Congo languages|Niger-Kordofanian languages]]\n*<tt>nub</tt> [[Nubian languages]]\n*<tt>oto</tt> [[Otomian languages]]\n*<tt>paa</tt> [[Papuan languages]]\n*<tt>phi</tt> [[Philippine languages]]\n*<tt>pra</tt> [[Prakrit languages]]\n*<tt>roa</tt> [[Romance languages]]\n*<tt>sai</tt> [[South American Indian languages]]\n*<tt>sal</tt> [[Salishan languages]]\n*<tt>sem</tt> [[Semitic languages]]\n*<tt>sgn</tt> [[sign language]]s\n*<tt>sio</tt> [[Siouan languages]]\n*<tt>sit</tt> [[Sino-Tibetan languages]]\n*<tt>sla</tt> [[Slavic languages]]\n*<tt>smi</tt> [[Sami languages]]\n*<tt>son</tt> [[Songhai languages]]\n*<tt>ssa</tt> [[Nilo-Saharan languages]]\n*<tt>tai</tt> [[Tai languages]]\n*<tt>tup</tt> [[Tupi languages]]\n*<tt>tut</tt> [[Altaic languages]]\n*<tt>wak</tt> [[Wakashan languages]]\n*<tt>wen</tt> [[Sorbian languages]]\n*<tt>ypk</tt> [[Yupik languages]]\n*<tt>znd</tt> [[Zande languages]]\n}}\n\n===Reserved for local use===\nThe interval from '''qaa''' to '''qtz''' is 'reserved for local use' and is not used in ISO 639-2 nor in [[ISO_639-3#Special_codes|ISO 639-3]]. These codes are typically used privately for languages not (yet) in either standard.\n\n===Special situations===\nThere are four generic codes for special situations:\n*'''mis''' is listed as \"uncoded languages\" (originally an abbreviation for \"miscellaneous\")\n*'''mul''' (for multiple languages) is applied when several languages are used and it is not practical to specify all the appropriate language codes\n*'''und''' (for undetermined) is used in situations in which a language or languages must be indicated but the language cannot be identified.\n*'''zxx''' is listed in the code list as \"no linguistic content\", e.g. animal sounds (added 2006-01-11)\nThese four codes are also used in [[ISO_639-3#Special_codes|ISO 639-3]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of ISO 639-2 codes]]\n*[[Language code]]\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.loc.gov/standards/iso639-2/}}\n*[https://www.loc.gov/standards/iso639-2/php/code_changes.php ISO 639-2/RA Change Notice] at the [[Library of Congress]]\n*[https://www.iso.org/standard/4767.html ISO 639-2:1998: Codes for the representation of names of languages\u2014Part 2: Alpha-3 code] at the [[International Organization for Standardization]]\n\n\n{{Footer ISO 639}}\n{{ISO standards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iso 639-2}}\n[[Category:ISO 639]]\n[[Category:1989 introductions]]\n[[Category:Language identifiers]]\n", "name_user": "SMcCandlish", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCollections of languages:The <tt> element hasn't existed in HTML since the 1990s.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_639-2"}
{"title_page": "Minute Man Air Field", "text_new": "{{Infobox airport\n| name                = Minute Man Air Field\n| image               = File:Arial Photo of Minute Man Air Field.jpg\n| caption             = Aerial Photo of Minute Man Air Field\n| FAA                 = 6B6\n| IATA                = MMN<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iata.org/publications/Pages/code-search.aspx|title=Airline and Airport Code Search| publisher=[[International Air Transport Association|IATA]]|accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref>\n| type                = Public\n| owner               = Minute Man Airfield, Inc.\n| operator            = Don McPherson\n| city-served         = Stow\n| location            = [[Stow, Massachusetts]]\n| elevation-m         = 82\n| elevation-f         = 268\n| coordinates         = {{coord|42|27|38|N|071|31|04|W|region:US-MA|display=inline,title}}\n| website             = {{URL|http://www.minutemanairfield.com/}}\n| pushpin_map         = USA Massachusetts\n| pushpin_label       = '''6B6'''\n| pushpin_mapsize     = 250\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location of airport in Massachusetts\n| r1-number           = 3/21\n| r1-length-m         = 844\n| r1-length-f         = 2,770\n| r1-surface          = [[Asphalt]]\n| r2-number           = 12/30\n| r2-length-m         = 488\n| r2-length-f         = 1,600\n| r2-surface          = [[Grass|Turf]]/[[Gravel]]\n| stat-year           = 2009\n| stat1-header        = Aircraft operations\n| stat1-data          = 48,095\n| stat2-header        = Based aircraft\n| stat2-data          = 67\n| footnotes           = Source: [[Federal Aviation Administration]]<ref name=FAA>{{FAA-airport|ID=6B6|use=PU|own=PR|site=09316.*A}}, retrieved 2009-12-30</ref>\n}}\n'''Minute Man Air Field''' {{Airport codes|MMN||6B6}} is a public-use [[airport]] located at 302 Boxboro Road, [[Stow, Massachusetts|Stow]], [[Massachusetts]], [[United States]]. The airport is privately owned by Minute Man Airfield, Inc.<ref name=FAA />\n\nStarted as a 1700&nbsp;ft grass landing strip known as Erikson Field in 1963 by local pilots, the airport was purchased by Paul McPherson in 1966. Paul and his son, Don, paved and extended the 2000 foot runway, added a parallel taxiway, tie-downs for 50 planes, installed AVGAS pumps and constructed the Operations Building. The former grass strip was re-opened as Minute Man Air Field on July 1, 1969. Paul's wife and daughter also opened a small coffee shop on the field called \"Peg's Place\" later on.<ref name=About>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://minutemanairfield.com/about/|website=Minute Man Air field|accessdate=October 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOver the decades, the airport has added aircraft maintenance and storage hangars, a runway extension, a second \"cross-wind\" runway, and aircraft parking aprons. In the early 1990s, 100 acres of land, was added to the field's land holdings instead of becoming a housing development. The open space is being farmed and serves as home to many species of wildlife.<ref name=\"About\"/> This acreage has recently been sold and is the site of a proposed 55+ \"active adult\" neighborhood consisting of 60+ housing units.\n\nMinute Man now has a 2800-foot paved-lighted-instrumented runway and a 1600-foot gravel-visual runway.\n\nThe airfield is home to more than 60 based aircraft including 3 helicopters stored in four hangars and on tie-downs along the taxi-ways and aprons. In addition to Nancy's Air Field Caf\u00e9, reputed as a fly-in or drive-in destination for fine food and friendly service, the airport is home to numerous other businesses.\n\nThe airport is still owned and operated by Don McPherson, and the operations are overseen by a board of Airport Commissioners. The Board is made up of local business, government, and aviation professionals who voluntarily serve as Commissioners.<gallery>\nFile:Approach to Runway 3 at 6B6.jpg|Dusk approach into runway 3 at Minute Man Airfield in a Cessna 172 with the runway lights visible.\n</gallery>\n\n== Facilities and aircraft ==\nMinute Man Air Field covers an area of {{convert|225|acre|ha|lk=on}} which contains two [[runway]]s:<ref name=FAA />\n* Runway 3/21: 2,770 x 48&nbsp;ft (844 x 15 m), Surface: Asphalt\n* Runway 12/30: 1,600 x 70&nbsp;ft (488 x 21 m), Surface: Turf/Gravel\n\nFor 12-month period ending 08/01/2009 the airport had 48,095 aircraft operations, an average of 132 per day: 99% [[general aviation]], &lt;1% [[air taxi]] and &lt;1% military. There are 67 aircraft based at this airport: 60 single engine, 1 multi engine, 3 [[helicopter]]s and 3 [[ultralight]].<ref name=FAA />\n\nThe runway was repaved (to meet FAA required standards for safety) in the summer of 2015. The work also included removing a small hill which was a danger to people in airplanes landing from the south.<ref>[http://minutemanairfield.com/july-2015-notam/ Minuteman Airfield] Don's Blog July 2015 NOTAM</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.minutemanairfield.com/ Airport website]\n* [http://www.nancysairfieldcafe.com/ Nancy's Air Field Cafe]\n{{US-airport-minor|6B6}}\n\n{{MA Airport}}\n\n[[Category:Stow, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Airports in Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox airport\n| name                = Minute Man Air Field\n| image               = File:Arial Photo of Minute Man Air Field.jpg\n| caption             = Aerial Photo of Minute Man Air Field\n| FAA                 = 6B6\n| IATA                = MMN<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iata.org/publications/Pages/code-search.aspx|title=Airline and Airport Code Search| publisher=[[International Air Transport Association|IATA]]|accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref>\n| type                = Public\n| owner               = Minute Man Airfield, Inc.\n| operator            = Don McPherson\n| city-served         = Stow\n| location            = [[Stow, Massachusetts]]\n| elevation-m         = 82\n| elevation-f         = 268\n| coordinates         = {{coord|42|27|38|N|071|31|04|W|region:US-MA|display=inline,title}}\n| website             = {{URL|http://www.minutemanairfield.com/}}\n| pushpin_map         = USA Massachusetts\n| pushpin_label       = '''6B6'''\n| pushpin_mapsize     = 250\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location of airport in Massachusetts\n| r1-number           = 3/21\n| r1-length-m         = 844\n| r1-length-f         = 2,770\n| r1-surface          = [[Asphalt]]\n| r2-number           = 12/30\n| r2-length-m         = 488\n| r2-length-f         = 1,600\n| r2-surface          = [[Grass|Turf]]/[[Gravel]]\n| stat-year           = 2009\n| stat1-header        = Aircraft operations\n| stat1-data          = 48,095\n| stat2-header        = Based aircraft\n| stat2-data          = 67\n| footnotes           = Source: [[Federal Aviation Administration]]<ref name=FAA>{{FAA-airport|ID=6B6|use=PU|own=PR|site=09316.*A}}, retrieved 2009-12-30</ref>\n}}\n'''Minute Man Air Field''' {{Airport codes|MMN||6B6}} is a public-use [[airport]] located at 302 Boxboro Road, [[Stow, Massachusetts|Stow]], [[Massachusetts]], [[United States]]. The airport is privately owned by Minute Man Airfield, Inc.<ref name=FAA />\n\nStarted as a 1700&nbsp;ft grass landing strip known as Erikson Field in 1963 by local pilots, the airport was purchased by Paul McPherson in 1966. Paul and his son, Don, paved and extended the 2000 foot runway, added a parallel taxiway, tie-downs for 50 planes, installed AVGAS pumps and constructed the Operations Building. The former grass strip was re-opened as Minute Man Air Field on July 1, 1969. Paul's wife and daughter also opened a small coffee shop on the field called \"Peg's Place\" later on.<ref name=About>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://minutemanairfield.com/about/|website=Minute Man Air field|accessdate=October 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOver the decades, the airport has added aircraft maintenance and storage hangars, a runway extension, a second \"cross-wind\" runway, and aircraft parking aprons. In the early 1990s, 100 acres of land, was added to the field's land holdings instead of becoming a housing development. The open space is being farmed and serves as home to many species of wildlife.<ref name=\"About\"/> This acreage has recently been sold and is the site of a proposed 55+ \"active adult\" neighborhood consisting of 60+ housing units.\n\nMinute Man now has a 2800-foot paved-lighted-instrumented runway and a 1600-foot gravel-visual runway.\n\nThe airfield is home to more than 60 based aircraft including 3 helicopters stored in four hangars and on tie-downs along the taxi-ways and aprons. In addition to Nancy's Air Field Caf\u00e9, reputed as a fly-in or drive-in destination for fine food and friendly service, the airport is home to numerous other businesses.\n\nThe airport is still owned and operated by Don McPherson, and the operations are overseen by a board of Airport Commissioners. The Board is made up of local business, government, and aviation professionals who voluntarily serve as Commissioners.<gallery>\nFile:Approach to Runway 3 at 6B6.jpg|Dusk approach into runway 3 at Minute Man Airfield in a Cessna 172 with the runway lights visible.\n</gallery>\n\n== Facilities and aircraft ==\nMinute Man Air Field covers an area of {{convert|225|acre|ha|lk=on}} which contains two [[runway]]s:<ref name=FAA />\n* Runway 3/21: 2,770 x 48&nbsp;ft (844 x 15 m), Surface: Asphalt\n* Runway 12/30: 1,600 x 70&nbsp;ft (488 x 21 m), Surface: Turf/Gravel\n\nFor 12-month period ending 08/01/2009 the airport had 48,095 aircraft operations, an average of 132 per day: 99% [[general aviation]], &lt;1% [[air taxi]] and &lt;1% military. There are 67 aircraft based at this airport: 60 single engine, 1 multi engine, 3 [[helicopter]]s and 3 [[ultralight]].<ref name=FAA />\n\nThe runway was repaved (to meet FAA required standards for safety) in the summer of 2015. The work also included removing a small hill which was a danger to people in airplanes landing from the south.<ref>[http://minutemanairfield.com/july-2015-notam/ Minuteman Airfield] Don's Blog July 2015 NOTAM</ref>\n\n==Flight School==\nAptis Aviation is a part 61 flight school based on Minute Man Air Field. They are the only flight school on the airport, and have been in business since November 2014 taking over after Noble Airventures left the field. They operate 5 rental planes, 3 club planes, and one simulator. The school is staffed with 2 full-time instructors, and a few part-time instructors. Their Chief [[Flight Instructor]], Devan Wiebe, earned the FAA Gold Seal Flight Instructor Certificate in August 2015. In addition to offering Private, instrument, and commercial instruction, Aptis Aviation can facilitate the training required to obtain the Tail Wheel and Complex aircraft endorsements. Two ground schools are run through the school, one geared towards private pilot students and one for instrument students. These classes run on request of the students provided there is enough demand.\n\n===Fleet===\n'''Rental Aircraft'''<ref name=\"Aptis Planes\">{{cite web|title=Private Plane Rentals|url=http://aptisaviation.com/services/plane-rental/|website=Aptis Aviation|accessdate=25 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105013839/http://aptisaviation.com/services/plane-rental/|archivedate=5 November 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Cessna 150]]m (N9230U)\n*[[Cessna 172]]m (N6835H)\n*[[Cessna 172RG]] (N6542V)\n*[[Aeronca Champion]] (N1060E)\n\n'''Aptis Access Club'''\n*[[Cessna 172]]m (N9014H)\n*[[Diamond DA40]] (N500NA)\n*[[Piper PA-28 Cherokee|Piper PA-28]] (N3768T)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.minutemanairfield.com/ Airport website]\n* [http://www.nancysairfieldcafe.com/ Nancy's Air Field Cafe]\n* [http://aptisaviation.com/ Aptis Aviation]\n{{US-airport-minor|6B6}}\n\n{{MA Airport}}\n\n[[Category:Stow, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Airports in Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Dubdub222", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed information", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minute_Man_Air_Field"}
{"title_page": "J\u00f3zef Retinger", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Polish diplomat and activist}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger\n|image             = File:Jozef Retinger.jpg\n|image_size        = \n|caption           = J\u00f3zef Retinger, recovering from a poisoning attempt c.1944<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n|birth_date        = {{birth date|1888|04|17|df=y}}\n|birth_place       = [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]]\n|death_date        = {{death date and age|df=yes|1960|06|12|1888|04|17}}\n|death_place       = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n|citizenship       = Polish\n|nationality       = Polish\n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = Economics, international relations, politics\n|work_institutions = [[Sorbonne University]] Phd, [[London School of Economics]], [[Polish government-in-exile]]\n|doctoral_advisor  =\n|doctoral_students =\n|known_for         = [[Bilderberg Group]], [[European Movement International]]\n|author_abbrev_bot =\n|author_abbrev_zoo =\n|influences        = [[Jesuits]], [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]]\n|influenced        = [[Joseph Conrad]], foundation of [[European Union]], the [[Bilderberg Group]]\n|prizes            = [[Nobel Peace Prize]] Nomination 1958\n|footnotes         =\n|signature         =\n}}\n'''J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger''' ([[Krak\u00f3w]], 17 April 1888 {{spaced ndash}} 12 June 1960, [[London]]; [[World War II]] [[nom de guerre|noms de guerre]] ''Salamandra'', \"Salamander\", and ''Brzoza'', \"Birch Tree\") was a [[Poles|Polish]] scholar, international political activist with access to some of the leading power brokers of the 20th century, a publicist and writer.\n\nAlready as a gifted student in [[Paris]] and [[London]] he mixed with the leading lights of music and literature. Most notably, he became a friend of compatriot [[Joseph Conrad]].<ref name = \"JR\">{{cite book|title=Joseph Retinger - Memoirs of an Eminence Grise|editor=John Pomian|publisher=Sussex University Press/ Chatto & Windus|date= 1972|url=https://ia800905.us.archive.org/5/items/MemoirsOfAnEminenceGrise1972/Memoirs%20of%20an%20Eminence%20Grise%2C%201972.pdf}}</ref> During [[World War I]], the young Retinger became politically active in [[Austria-Hungary]] and [[Russian Empire|Russia]] on behalf of the Polish independence movement. Following a failed attempt to broker peace between Austria-Hungary and the [[Allies of World War I]], he had to retreat to [[Central America]], where he became an economic adviser.\n\nAfter the outbreak of [[World War II]], he was principal adviser to the [[Polish government-in-exile]]. Early in 1944, a daring mission into [[Occupied Poland]] by parachute, with the help of British intelligence, added to his air of mystery and subsequent controversy.<ref name=\"Oleks\">{{cite web|title=The Most Mysterious Man in 20th-Century Politics|author=Oleksiak, Wojciech|publisher=Culture.pl|date=2016-12-14|url=https://culture.pl/en/article/the-most-mysterious-man-in-20th-century-politics|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> A Freemason with a reputation as a [[grey eminence]], after World War II he went on to cofound the [[European Movement]], which led to establishment of the [[European Union]], and was instrumental in forming the secretive [[Bilderberg Group]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pieczewski|first1=Andrzej|title=Joseph Retinger's conception of and contribution to the early process of European integration|journal=European Review of History|date=11 Aug 2010|volume=17|issue=4|pages=581\u2013604|doi=10.1080/13507486.2010.495766}}</ref> In 1958 he was nominated for the [[Nobel Peace Prize]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Emilian Czyrnia\u0144ski.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Emilian Czyrnia\u0144ski]], Retinger's maternal grandfather, 1878 photo by [[Walery Rzewuski]]]]\n[[File:Wierchy-1925---W\u0142adys\u0142aw-Zamoyski-(1853-1924).png|thumb|150px|[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]] (1853-1924)]]\n[[File:Misa Sert.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Misia Sert|Misia Godebska Sert]], Retinger's Parisian cousin]]\nJ\u00f3zef Retinger was born in [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Poland]] (then part of [[Austria-Hungary]]), the youngest of five children: his father had a daughter, Aniela, from a first marriage to Helena Jawornicka.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\">{{cite web|title=J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|url=https://kangur.uek.krakow.pl//biblioteka/retinger/B.%20Podgorski%20-%20J.H.%20Retinger%201888-1960.pdf|lang=pl|page=5|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> His mother was Maria Krystyna [[Emil Czyrnia\u0144ski|Czyrnia\u0144ska]], daughter of a [[Greek Catholic Church|Greek Catholic]] [[Lemkos|Lemko]] professor of chemistry at the [[Jagiellonian University]]. His father, J\u00f3zef Stanis\u0142aw Retinger, was the personal legal counsel and successful adviser to French-born Count [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]]. Retinger's great grandfather, Filip Rettinger, was a Jewish tailor from [[Tarn\u00f3w]] who with his family converted to Catholicism in 1827.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Sypek, Antoni|title=\u017bydowskie konwersje na chrze\u015bcija\u0144stwo w Tarnowie, w latach 1785-1900|journal= Rocznik Tarnowski|date= 2013| page= 128|trans-title= Jewish conversions to christianity in Tarn\u00f3w in 1785-1900}}</ref> When his lawyer grandson died, Count Zamoyski took the promising youngster, J\u00f3zef, into his household and paid for him to attend the [[Bart\u0142omiej Nowodworski High School]] in Krak\u00f3w. Retinger's eldest brother, Emil, became a commander in the [[Polish Navy]], while his son, {{Interlanguage link|Witold Retinger|pl}}, was stationed in the [[United Kingdom]] during [[World War II]] (1943\u201345), as a member then leader of [[No. 308 Polish Fighter Squadron|Squadron 308]] of the [[Polish Air Forces in France and Great Britain|Polish Air Force]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafweb.org/Squadrons/Sqn300-318.htm|title=History of No.'s 300\u2013318 Squadrons at RAF Web|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Retinger's brother, Juliusz, taught [[physiological chemistry]] at the [[University of Chicago]] and [[University of Wilno]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Polish Biographical Dictionary|title-link= Polish Biographical Dictionary|volume= 127|page= 152|lang=pl}}</ref> Retinger himself initially considered a career in the priesthood, but three months in the Jesuit [[novitiate]] in [[Rome]] confirmed he would not be suited to the life.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n\nFurther financed by Count Zamoyski in 1906, Retinger entered simultaneously the [[Ecole des sciences politiques]] and the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]] in [[Paris]] and two years later, aged twenty, became the youngest person ever to earn a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in literature from there.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> While in the French capital, armed with introductions from Zamoyski and his own relative, the salonni\u00e8re and pianist [[Misia Sert]], he moved in intellectual circles and was befriended by among others, [[Andr\u00e9 Gide]], [[Fran\u00e7ois Mauriac]], {{ill|Bernard Grasset (publisher)|lt=Bernard Grasset|fr|Bernard Grasset (\u00e9diteur)}}, [[Jean Giraudoux]], [[Erik Satie]] and [[Maurice Ravel]]. His early literary ambitions were stopped in their tracks when he presented his first novel, ''\"Les Souffleurs\"'' to Andr\u00e9 Gide for his opinion. Gide told him: ''Joseph, you will never be a writer.''<ref name = \"JR\"/>{{rp|pages=11\u201313}}\n\nHe next went to [[Munich]] to study [[comparative psychology]] for a year. From there, encouraged by Zamoyski, in 1910 he moved to [[England]], where he entered the [[London School of Economics]] for a year's study and began a lobbying operation on behalf of the Polish cause and its populations scattered across three ailing empires. Formally he became Director of the London Office of the Polish National Committee (1912\u20131914).<ref>{{cite web|title=Jozef Retinger - cv|url=https://www.cvce.eu/en/obj/joseph_retinger-en-9d454c22-957c-49ef-8c7b-be5f98d676fc.htmlE|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|first1=Wojciech|last1=Roszkowski|first2=Jan|last2=Kofman|title=Biographical Dictionary of Central and Eastern Europe in the Twentieth Century|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date=2016|isbn=9781317475934|chapter-url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=RnKlDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA2377|access-date=2017-07-25|chapter=Retinger J\u00f3zef}}</ref> During this time he continued to move in \u00e9lite circles and  thanks to an introduction by [[Arnold Bennett]] whom he had met in Paris, Retinger developed a close friendship with his older Polish compatriot, the already well established novelist, [[Joseph Conrad]].<ref name=\":0\"/> Retinger urged Conrad to visit Poland, and on 28 July 1914, the day [[World War I]] broke out, Retinger, his wife Otolia, and Conrad, his wife, and their two sons arrived in Krak\u00f3w, the two men's childhood stamping grounds (they were alumni of the same [[secondary school]]). Due to the closeness of the Russian border (Russia was then allied to Great Britain), the Conrads soon sought greater safety in the [[Tatra Mountains]] resort of [[Zakopane]].<ref>[[Zdzis\u0142aw Najder]], ''Joseph Conrad: A Life'', Rochester, New York, Camden House, 2007, {{ISBN|978-1-57113-347-2}}, pp. 459\u201363.</ref> Retinger would write about Conrad in his 1943 book, ''Conrad and His Contemporaries''. Historian [[Norman Davies]] suggests that it was probably Conrad who introduced the \"polyglot and polymath\" Retinger to the British intelligence services.<ref name=\"Davies\">{{cite book|author=Davies, Norman|title=Rising '44: The Battle for Warsaw|title-link=Rising '44|year=2003|place= London|publisher= Pan Books|isbn=0-333-90568-7| page= 53}}</ref> Later Retinger became a personal friend of Major-General Sir [[Colin Gubbins]], wartime head of [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]], and after the war an [[Special Intelligence Service|MI6]] \"asset\".<ref name=\"wilford\">{{cite book|title=The CIA, the British Left and the Cold War: Calling the Tune? Studies in Intelligence|author= Wilford, Hugh|publisher=Routledge|date= 2013|page=242|isbn=978-1135294779}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Dorril, Stephen|title= A Critical Review: MI6: Fifty years of special operations. Doctoral thesis|publisher= University of Huddersfield|date=2010|url=http://eprints.hud.ac.uk/id/eprint/9763/1/sdorrilfinalthesis.pdf|page=27}}</ref>\n\n===World War I===\n[[File:Joseph Conrad author.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Joseph Conrad]]]]\nWith the clouds of war closing in, the project of writing a play together with Conrad based on the latter's novel, ''[[Nostromo]]'' had to be abandoned as both men hurriedly left Austria Hungary. Retinger would have been eligible for military call up in [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]], but no mention of this is made by his biographers. Instead, he put aside literary endeavours and once more assumed the role of a political lobbyist for Poland, publishing pamphlets and travelling between London, Paris and [[New York City|New York]], aided by Conrad in London.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=10}} In the first years of the war, this was not on the agenda of the major powers. Retinger looked instead for other potential alliances and political leverage which led to meetings with leading [[Zionism|Zionists]] of the time, including [[Chaim Weizmann]], [[Vladimir Zhabotinski]] and [[Nahum Sokolow]] who were seeking international recognition and rights for the [[Jewish diaspora]].<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=11}} In 1916 guided by Zamoyski and with the approval of [[Herbert Asquith]], [[David Lloyd George]] and [[Georges Clemenceau]] with his old Parisian connections, [[Prince Sixtus of Bourbon-Parma|Sixtus]] and [[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Xavier de Bourbon Parme]], the Duchess of Montebello and Marquis [[Boni de Castellane]], as well as Zamoyski's friend the Polish [[General of the Jesuits]], [[Wlodimir Led\u00f3chowski|W\u0142odzimierz Led\u00f3chowski]], Retinger became a \"courier\" in the secretive European dynastic negotiation suing for peace with Austria.<ref name= \"Kultura\">{{cite journal|author=Jele\u0144ski, K.A.|title=Prekursor anachroniczny|journal=[[Kultura|Kultura Paryska]]|location=Paris|date=1961|lang=pl|trans-title= Anachronistic Precursor (Obituary)|pages=190\u2013193|url=http://static.kulturaparyska.com/attachments/51/96/79311ebf90d26ec65a78e3b802589c43f76cb880.pdf#page=97}}</ref> It became known as the ''[[Sixtus Affair]]'' but was a failure, due to Germany's refusal to cooperate thus making Austria more dependent on it.<ref>{{cite book|title=Informal Alliance: The Bilderberg Group and Transatlantic Relations during the Cold War, 1952-1968|series=  Routledge Studies in Modern History|author=Gijswijt, Thomas W.|chapter=J\u00f3zef Retinger - Informal diplomat|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date= 2018|isbn=978-1-3511-8102-0}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1 = Demblin, August | author2 = Demblin, Alexander | title = Minister gegen Kaiser : Aufzeichnungen eines \u00f6sterreichisch-ungarischen Diplomaten \u00fcber Aussenminister Czernin und Kaiser Karl |lang= de| date = 1997 | publisher = B\u00f6hlau | place = Vienna | isbn = 3-205-98762-4 | trans-title=Minister versus Kaiser: The designs of an Austro-Hungarian Diplomat to outwit Foreign Minister Czernin and [[Charles I of Austria|Kaiser Charles]]}}</ref> In 1917 he met [[Boy Capel|Arthur \"Boy\" Capel]], the half-French dilettante, polo player and \"sponsor\" of [[Coco Chanel]]. Capel is said to have planted in Retinger's mind the idea of a world federal government based on an Anglo-French alliance.<ref>{{cite journal|author= Biskupski, M. B.|title= Spy, Patriot or Internationalist? The Early Career of J\u00f3zef Retinger, Polish Patriarch of the European Union|journal= The Polish Review, Vol. 43, No. 1|date= 1998|pages= 23\u201367}}</ref> After concerns for his personal safety due to his \"political meddling\" in Austria-Hungary and in the emergent [[Soviet Union]], in 1918 Retinger was banned from France, and sought sanctuary in [[Spain]] for several months.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=12}}\n\n==Mexican years==\n[[File:Jane Anderson 1917.JPG|thumb|left|150px|US journalist [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]] 1917]] \nHe travelled on to [[Cuba]] and then to [[Mexico]], where he became an unofficial political adviser to union organizer [[Luis Morones]] whom he fortuitously met crossing the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]], and to President [[Plutarco El\u00edas Calles]].<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/><ref name=\"Oleks\"/> A glimpse of Retinger, newly divorced and love lorn for the American journalist, [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]], appears in the biography of another American woman, the communist sympathiser [[Katherine Anne Porter]], a member of the Morones circle. In it he is described as a \"Polish intriguer\" and \"British Marxist\". In 1921 while on an obscure mission to the [[United States]] to buy saddles, Retinger was arrested and imprisoned in [[Laredo, Texas|Laredo]] and Porter was despatched from Mexico to get him released.<ref name= \"Stout\">{{cite book|title=Katherine Anne Porter: A Sense of the Times - Minds of the new South|author=Stout, Janis P.|publisher=University of Virginia Press|date= 1995|pages=47\u201351|isbn= 978-0-813915685}}</ref> That same year Retinger had proposed that Katherine Porter and her friend Mary Doherty accompany him to Europe to do \"collaborative work\", an offer that was spurned.<ref name= \"Stout\"/>{{rp|pages=94\u201395}} Retinger helped advance Mexico's nationalization of its oil industry in 1928.<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\">{{cite journal|author=Ethridge, Marcus E.|title= Review of M.B.B. Biskupski, \"War and Diplomacy in East and West: A Biography of J\u00f3zef Retinger\", London, Routledge, 2017, ISBN: 978-1-138-21845-1|journal= [[The Polish Review]]| volume= 64|date= 2019|issue= 1| page= 95|doi= 10.5406/polishreview.64.1.0094}} Ethridge's full review is on pp. 94\u201395</ref> His activities in Mexico lasted a total of almost seven years and only ended with Calles's fall from power in 1936. They inspired Retinger to write three volumes on the tumultuous events of that Latin American republic.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/> The Mexican years were punctuated by trips back to Europe where he took on the role of Representative in the United Kingdom of the Polish Socialist Party (1924\u20131928). In 1926 he married his second wife, Stella, with whom he travelled to Mexico on one occasion. After her death in 1933 his two daughters were left in the care of their maternal grandmother and were estranged from him until the 1950s.\n\nIn the rest of the interwar period, he published many contributions in periodicals, such as the Polish ''Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie'' (Literary News) (see [[Wiadomo\u015bci (London magazine)|Wiadomo\u015bci]]), on literary and political subjects.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/><ref>{{cite journal|title=Hitleryzm czyli bolszewizm|author=Retinger, J.H.|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie|date=1939-03-12|url=http://retropress.pl/wiadomosci-literackie/hitleryzm-czyli-bolszewizm/|issue=11 (803), year 16|lang=pl|trans-title=Hitlerism equals Bolshevism}}</ref>\n\n==Building blocks on the table==\n[[File:W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski, 1923.jpg|thumb|150px|[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]], Polish prime minister in 1923]]\nDuring [[World War II]], Retinger who was in [[London]], was involved in arranging for Polish troops to be transferred to Britain from France. He was bidden by Winston Churchill personally to escort [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]] by plane to England from France which had just capitulated to the invading Germans.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=16}} He became principal adviser and confidant to the Prime Minister of the [[Polish Government in Exile]] now re-established in London.<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>{{rp|page= 95}}<ref>{{cite web|title=London Gazette|date=1942-12-04|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/35811/page/5301/data.pdf|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> In fact, their political relationship went back to 1916 and was strengthened during [[Wladyslaw Sikorski]]'s earlier brief stint as prime minister, 1922-23 in newly independent Poland, and came to greater fruition when both men were later in exile in London.<ref name=\"Lane\">{{cite book|title=Poland and European Integration: The Ideas and Movements of Polish Exiles in the West, 1939\u201391|author1=Lane, Thomas |author2=Wolanski, Marian|publisher=Springer|date= 2009|page=18|isbn=978-0-2302-71784}}</ref>\n\nSikorski's dependence on Retinger was the greater as he did not have mastery of [[English language|English]]. At this time Retinger was despatched to talk with other exiled government representatives in London, who included [[Marcel-Henri Jaspar]], [[Paul Van Zeeland]], [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] in preparation for a post-war geopolitical landscape.<ref>{{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1|page=455}}</ref> He went on to posit a \"Sikorski Plan\" consisting of two stages, the first of which was signed in January 1942 and proposed a Polish-Czech confederation.<ref>{{cite book|author=Walter Lipgens|title=Documents on the history of European integration: Plans for European union in Great Britain and in exile, 1939\u20131945 (including 107 documents in their original languages on 3 microfiches)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X3TsVCAt9F4C&pg=PA648|accessdate=10 August 2011|year=1985|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-009724-5|page=648}}</ref> The idea was to expand it into a [[wikt:Central Europe|Central Europe]]an confederation with Poland and [[Lithuania]], [[Czechoslovakia]] as its nucleus around which would be grouped [[Romania]], [[Hungary]], Yugoslavia and [[Greece]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Schmidt, Andrea|title=From Intermarium to the Three Seas Initiative: The Implications of the Polish Orientation Over the Central and Eastern European Region on Hungarian Policy in Baltic-Black Sea Regionalisms: Patchworks and Networks at Europe's Eastern Margins|editor1=Bogdanova, Olga |editor2=Makarychev, Andrey|publisher=Springer Nature|date= 2019|page=157|isbn= 978-3-0302-48789}}</ref> The agenda behind this was to create a common political blue-print for smaller countries abutting larger European powers and became the basis of a Belgian-Dutch union which would mirror the Polish-Czech arrangement.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Together and Alone in Allied London: Czechoslovak, Norwegian and Polish Governments-in-Exile, 1940\u20131945|author=Jakubec, Pavol|journal=[[International History Review]]|date=2019|doi=10.1080/07075332.2019.1600156|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nThis scheme of Retinger's caused problems between London and [[Moscow]]. In order not to tread on Soviet toes, the British altered their position and refused to back Sikorski's negotiations with the eight smaller European states. In his speech on the Council of Europe, [[Winston Churchill]] [https://www.winstonchurchill.org/resources/speeches/1941-1945-war-leader/national-address/ BBC radio broadcast] on 21 March 1943 referred to the necessity of smaller nations forming groupings, but that it was too early to go into detail. The most Retinger was able to achieve was to push through the [[Sikorski-Mayski Agreement]], signed on 30 July 1941, which provided for the formation of the [[Anders' army]], thus ridding Stalin of the immediate human problem posed by the hundreds of thousands of Polish [[Prisoner of war|POW]]s and deportees from the [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u201345)|Soviet occupied]] [[Kresy Zachodnie|Kresy]] regions of the former [[Second Polish Republic]], who after an arduous odyssey across thousands of miles would eventually end up as the [[United Kingdom]]'s human problem.<ref>{{cite book|author=Anders, Lt.-General W\u0142adys\u0142aw|title= An Army in Exile|publisher= MacMillan & Co. Ltd|date=1949|page=73}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Polish Underground Army, the Western Allies, and the Failure of Strategic Unity in World War II|author=Peszke, Michael Alfred|publisher=McFarland|date= 2015|isbn=978-1-4766-10276|page=70}}</ref> This trade-off adumbrated the [[Tehran Conference|Tehran]] and [[Yalta Conference]]s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Identity in Flux. The Polish Community in Britain|author=Sword, Keith|place=London|publisher=School of Slavonic and East European Studies - SSEES Occasional Papers No. 36| date=1996|isbn=0-903425-60-2|pages=24\u201330|url=https://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/id/eprint/10078280/1/SSEES0012.pdf|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Brushes with death==\nRetinger narrowly avoided perishing in the sea off [[Gibraltar]] with [[Wladyslaw Sikorski's death controversy|W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]], in July 1943, but for the fact that he was not needed to accompany the premier on a troop inspection in the Middle East and would be better employed in London. The spare seat on the plane went to Sikorski's daughter who died with her father.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> Retinger was devastated by this turn of events. His relationship with Sikorski's successor, [[Stanislaw Mikolajczyk]] was much more ambivalent, but he obtained his consent for a special mission to Poland under [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]] in April 1944.<ref>Bu\u0142hak, W\u0142adys\u0142aw. \"The Foreign Office and the [[Special Operations Executive]] and the Expedition of J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger to Poland, April\u2013July 1944\", ''[[The Polish Review]]'', vol. 61, no. 3, 2016, pp. 33\u201357.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Members of the Polish Government, Prime Minister's Office|publisher=the Gazette|location=Edinburgh|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/Edinburgh/issue/16118/page/134/data.pdf|page=184|date=1944-04-21|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nWith an SOE brief and without prior training, Retinger, aged 56, parachuted into [[German-occupied Poland|occupied Poland]] with 2nd Lt. [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt]], (see [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt#Operation \"Salamander\"|Operation Salamander]]), to meet with Polish underground figures, to deliver money to the Polish underground, and to \"explain to his fellow Poles in the homeland 'how are we going to lose this war'\".<ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\">{{cite book|last1=Eringer|first1=Robert|author-link=Robert Eringer|title=The Global Manipulators|publisher=Pentacle Books|asin=B00546KTEM|oclc=26551991}}</ref>{{rp|pages=16\u201322}} <ref name = \"JR\"/>{{rp|page=265}}<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>  Following at least one assassination attempt on him, Retinger expressed his frustration thus:\n\n{{blockquote|You know why I came.  The [Underground] [[Government Delegation for Poland|Delegate]] knows as well.... They know that I only want to convince them that it will be necessary in the future to cooperate with the Communists, because no English are coming here, only Russians.  If we do not get along with them somehow, it will be a terrible tragedy, because we well know what [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]] and the [[NKVD]] [Interior Ministry of the Soviet Union] are. And it's about trying to make people here understand this fact. And they want to murder me!}}<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>\n\nThe latter quip was a reference to elements in the [[Polish Underground Army]], the [[Armia Krajowa|AK]] who were convinced Retinger was not serving the interests of his country and should therefore be \"removed\". One apparent attempt to liquidate him in Poland was on the grounds of a \"death sentence\" to be carried out on the alleged orders of general [[Kazimierz Sosnkowski]]. It was foiled by the intervention of an old friend and [[Armia Krajowa|AK fighter]], Tadeusz Gebethner.<ref>{{cite web|title=The story of Tadeusz Gebethner|url=https://sprawiedliwi.org.pl/en/stories-of-rescue/story-tadeusz-gebethner|publisher=sprawiedliwi.org.pl |access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> There was also an attempt during his visit in occupied Poland to poison him, which failed. On his return to London, he spent some time in the [[Dorchester Hotel]] in London's [[Park Lane, London|Park Lane]] recovering from his ordeal of the trip, which left him lame in one leg for the rest of his life, possibly due to the [[Polyneuritis]] brought on by the poison. His first visitor at the Dorchester was Sir [[Anthony Eden]], the foreign secretary.<ref name=\"Davies\"/><ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\"/>\n\nImmediately after the war, in 1945-6 Retinger travelled to [[Warsaw]] with emergency aid for the capital's population. It consisted largely of tons of British and US Army surplus, such as equipment, blankets and field-kitchens.<ref name= \"Kultura\"/> When his erstwhile military escort from \"operation Salamander\", [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt|Tadeusz Chciuk]] and his new wife, Ewa, were arrested in Poland as subversives by the Polish Communist security service, Retinger allegedly appealed over their heads directly to [[Vyacheslav Molotov|Molotov]] in [[Moscow]] to have them released. Apparently the personal intervention succeeded. In 1948 the Chciuks became refugees in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jozef Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Chciuk-Celt, Jan|url=http://pdf.amazingdiscoveries.org/References/RB/275%20PDFs/jozef-hieronim-retinger-slide-79.pdf|access-date=2020-03-03}} Jan Chciuk-Celt is the younger son of Tadeusz Chciuk, Retinger's military courier during \"Operation Saamander\" and was a co-author and editor of his father's war memoirs.</ref><ref>{{cite book|authors=[[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt|Marek Celt]], Jan Chciuk-Celt|title=Parachuting into Poland, 1944: Memoir of a Secret Mission with Jozef Retinger|publisher=McFarland|page=17|date= 2013|isbn=978-1-4766-03384}}</ref>\n\n===Unwanted intrusion===\nDark days followed World War II when tensions rose between former Western and Eastern allies and in April 1946 Retinger's flat in [[Bayswater]], West London, was broken into and his and his secretary's files ransacked by persons unknown. He reported the matter to [[Scotland Yard]], but the [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]] were not overly bothered. As a result, Retinger escalated his complaint and ended up being interviewed by the Britain's security services. His view was that the newly communist embassy of the [[Polish People's Republic]] were responsible for the break-in.<ref>{{cite book|author=Moss, Eloise|title=Night Raiders: Burglary and the Making of Modern Urban Life in London, 1860-1968|publisher=Oxford University Press|date= 2019|pages=186\u201387|isbn=978-0-1925-7677-4}}</ref>\n\nFrom the moment Winston Churchill had made his \"[[Iron Curtain]]\" speech in [[Fulton, Missouri]], in April 1946, Retinger turned his efforts to a modified European project he had harboured for decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.winstonchurchill.org/i4a/pages/index.cfm?pageid=429 |title=Sinews of Peace (Iron Curtain) |accessdate=2007-02-26 |last=Churchill |first=Winston |publisher=Churchill Centre |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070207054810/http://www.winstonchurchill.org/i4a/pages/index.cfm?pageid=429 |archivedate=7 February 2007 }}</ref><ref name= \"Kultura\"/>\n\n==Vision for Europe==\n[[File:Krakow-Jozef Retinger plaque.jpg|thumb|right|[[Krak\u00f3w]] plaque commemorating Retinger, \"great pioneer of European unity\".]]\nAfter World War II, Retinger feared another devastating war in Europe, this time fought between \"Russia\" and \"the Anglo-Saxons\".<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/> He became a leading advocate of [[European unification]] as a means of securing peace.<ref>{{cite web|author=Retinger, J. H.|title= The European Continent? Address given to the Royal Institute of Foreign Affairs in London|url=https://www.cvce.eu/content/publication/2008/2/19/534c684a-8924-445a-8181-58360f939f56/publishable_en.pdf|publisher=CVCE|date= 7 May 1946|access-date=2020-03-27}} Correction: although the original states Royal Institute of Foreign Affairs, it should read [[Royal Institute of International Affairs]], known today as \"[[Chatham House]]\", this is likely a copyediting error at CVCE (ed.).</ref> He helped found both the [[European Movement]] and the [[Council of Europe]], somewhat to the dismay of the philosopher Count [[Richard Coudenhove-Kalergi]], the post-[[World War I]] [[Anti-communism|anti-bolshevist]] founder of the [[Paneuropean Union]] movement.<ref name=\"wilford\"/>{{rp|pages=227\u2013228}}<ref>{{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1|page=165}}</ref>\n\nRetinger, with his connections in Holland, Belgium, and [[Switzerland]] (he was a friend of [[Denis de Rougemont]]), took his cue from [[Winston Churchill]]'s 1947 [[Zurich]] speech and found fertile ground with thirteen British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] members of Parliament who backed the idea of a loose European association of states. Working in particular with Britain's [[Duncan Sandys]], incidentally Churchill's son-in-law, he took on the lion's share of the work and became Honorary Secretary General of the [[European Movement]]. He organised the 1948 [[Congress of Europe|Hague Congress]] which brought together the two camps of those for a unified Europe and those in favour of a federal Europe.<ref name=\"Lane\"/> During the congress, Retinger networked assiduously among the delegates, who included the Vatican diplomat, [[Giovanni Montini]], the future [[Pope Paul VI]]. Ensuing discussions led eventually to the formation in 1951 of a [[European Coal and Steel Community]].<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n\n===Creator of Bilderberg===\nRetinger was the initiator and architect of the informal [[Bilderberg Group|Bilderberg]] conferences in 1952-54 and was their permanent secretary until his premature death in London in 1960. The original group which met in the eponymous Dutch hotel in 1954 was gathered by  Retinger and included [[David Rockefeller]], [[Denis Healey]] with [[Prince Bernhard of Lippe-Biesterfeld|Prince Bernhard of the Netherlands]], (a former SS officer), as chairman. The purpose was to stimulate understanding between Europe and the US as the Cold War developed by bringing together financiers, industrialists, politicians and opinion formers. All discussions were to be strictly under [[Chatham House Rule]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Bunting, Madeleine|title=Weekend break for the global elite|journal=[[The Guardian]]|date=2001-05-25}}</ref> A founding member of the group, later British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Foreign Secretary, Healey, described the secretive Bilderberg meetings as the \"brainchild\" of Retinger.<ref>{{cite web|title=Denis Healey on Bilderberg|url=https://www.worldsocialism.org/spgb/socialist-standard/2002/2000s/no-1175-july-2002/denis-healey-bilderberg/|publisher=worldsocialism.org|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Aubourg, Valerie|title=Organizing Atlanticism: the Bilderberg group and the Atlantic institute, 1952\u20131963|journal=[[Intelligence and National Security]]|volume=18, (2)|date=2003|pages= 92\u2013105 |doi=10.1080/02684520412331306760}}</ref>\n\nDespite eschewing any distinctions or medals throughout his life, in 1958 he was nominated for the Nobel Peace Prize.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.nobelprize.org/nomination/archive/show.php?id=15660 |title =Nomination for Nobel Peace Prize: Joseph Retinger |author =Nobelprize.org |publisher =Nobel Media AB 2014 |website = Nomination Database| date = |access-date = 2014-10-09}}</ref> He died in poverty of lung cancer.<ref name =\"BP\">{{cite web|title=J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|url=https://kangur.uek.krakow.pl//biblioteka/retinger/B.%20Podgorski%20-%20J.H.%20Retinger%201888-1960.pdf|lang=pl|page=53|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> He was buried at [[North Sheen Cemetery]] in the presence of five British cabinet ministers as well as of his two younger daughters who were finally reconciled with him.<ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\"/>{{rp|pages=16\u201322}} According to the oration of Sir [[Edward Beddington-Behrens]], Retinger not only had special access to [[10 Downing Street]] but also to the [[White House]].<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> \n[[File:Gr\u00f3b J\u00f3zefa Hieronima Retingera.jpg|thumb|right|Retinger's grave, [[North Sheen Cemetery]], London]]\nRetinger's long time personal assistant and the editor of his posthumous memoirs, John Pomian, actually {{Interlanguage link|Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz|pl}}, was another Polish emigr\u00e9 in London, later a director of the Heim gallery in London's [[St James's]], owned by the influential Polish art historian and philanthropist, [[Andrzej Ciechanowiecki]].<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://nekrologi.wyborcza.pl/0,11,,373783,Jan-Pomiana-B%C5%82awdziewicza-kondolencje.html | title =Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz | trans-title=Obituary of Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz|journal = Wyborcza.pl |date=2015| lang = pl | access-date = 2016-10-28}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRetinger married twice. In 1912 he wed the well-born Otolia Zubrzycka (divorced 1921, died 1984), with whom he had a daughter, Malina (later Puchalska). In 1926 he wed Stella Morel (died 1933), daughter of French-born pacifist and [[Dundee]] member of Parliament [[E.D. Morel]] and Mary, n\u00e9e Richardson, with whom he had two daughters, Maria (later Fforde) and Stasia (later French). Among his grandchildren are David French, and fantasy novelist, [[Jasper Fforde]].\n\nDuring the Great War and after, Retinger appears to have fallen under the spell of several women, especially the American journalist [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]], a supposed lover of Joseph Conrad.<ref name= \"JM\">{{cite book|title=Joseph Conrad: A Biography|author= Meyers, Jeffrey|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|date= 2001|page=361|isbn=978-0-8154-11123}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=The Athens Observer|first=Donald E.|last=Wilkes|title=Jane Anderson: The Nazi Georgia Peach|url=http://digitalcommons.law.uga.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1019&context=fac_pm|date=May 18, 1995|page=5|accessdate=24 August 2013}}</ref> Retinger's own liaison with Anderson brought about the breakdown of Retinger's marriage to Otolia and drove a wedge between him and his friend Conrad.<ref name= \"JM\"/>{{rp|page=293}} However Conrad biographer, John Stape, gives an alternative version for the cooling of relations between the two men, suggesting instead that as Retinger's enthusiasms were not shared by the novelist, shortly after the war, without his charming wife by his side, Retinger's proneness to exaggeration and tactlessness made him less socially acceptable.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Several Lives of Joseph Conrad|author= Stape, John|publisher=Random House|date= 2010|pages=187\u2013188|isbn=978-1409006824}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nOver the decades since his 1960 death, the left-leaning Retinger continues to draw fascination and controversy with his political skill, his apparently selfless single-mindedness, and his lasting institutional legacy in Europe and beyond.<ref>{{cite book|author=Wisnewski, Gerhard|title=The Bilderbergers Puppet-Masters of Power?: An Investigation into Claims of Conspiracy at the Heart of Politics, Business and the Media|translator=J. Collis|trans-title=Drahtzieher der Macht (2010)|date=2014|place=West Sussex|publisher=Clairview Books|isbn=978-1-90557075-1|pages=63\u201366}}</ref> [[Adam Pragier]], a notable Polish exile and trenchant political commentator (and a secondary-school contemporary of Retinger's), has described him as \"a sort of adventurer, but in the good sense of the word\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Czas przesz\u0142y dokonany - Czasy i ludzie|author= Pragier, Adam|work=Czas przesz\u0142y dokonany, Part 1|series= volume 7 of 100-lecie Niepodleg\u0142o\u015bci - 100th anniversary of Polish independence|editors=Friszke, Andrzej and Peja\u015b, Ewa|location=Warsaw|publisher=[[Museum of Polish History]]|date= 2018|isbn=978-8-3652-4829-9|orig-year=First published by B. \u015awiderski in London 1966|page=852|trans-title=The Past Perfect - Lives and Times}}</ref> On the other hand, detractors impugn his influence due to alleged connections, with deeply secret and malign factions, for which there is so far no reliable evidence.<ref>{{cite journal|author=K\u0119der, Wojciech|title=Recenzje: Bogdan Podg\u00f3rski, J\u00f3zef Retinger prywatny polityk, Universitas, Krak\u00f3w 2013, ss. 417.\n|journal=Studia Sandomierskie 23|date= 2016|pages=303\u2013314|lang=pl|trans-title=Review of Bogdan Podg\u00f3rski, ''J\u00f3zef Retinger private politician''. Krak\u00f3w: Universitas. 2013, pages 417.|url=https://journals.indexcopernicus.com/api/file/viewByFileId/84684.pdf}}\n</ref><ref>{{Cite web|author=Cornell, Svante E|title=Erbakan, K\u0131sak\u00fcrek, and the Mainstreaming of Extremism in Turkey |publisher=[[Hudson Institute]]|date=2018 |url=https://www.hudson.org/research/14375-erbakan-k-sak-rek-and-the-mainstreaming-of-extremism-in-turkey|access-date=2020-04-03}} see fn. 19.</ref> He remains an enigma, and probably the one substantial contributor to postwar European peace who has no physical monument.<ref name = \"BP\"/>{{rp|page=60}}\n\nIn 2000 [[The Daily Telegraph]]'s [[Ambrose Evans-Pritchard]] revealed, from declassified US Government records, that:\n{{blockquote|The leaders of the European Movement \u2013 Retinger, the visionary [[Robert Schuman]] and the former Belgian prime minister [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] \u2013 were all treated as hired hands by their American sponsors. The US role was handled as a covert operation. ACUE\u2019s funding came from the [[Ford Foundation|Ford]] and [[Rockefeller Foundation]]s as well as business groups with close ties to the US government.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/1356047/Euro-federalists-financed-by-US-spy-chiefs.html|title=Euro-federalists financed by US Spy Chief|author= Ambrose Evans-Pritchard|date=18 September 2000|publisher= The Daily Telegraph|author-link=Ambrose Evans-Pritchard}}</ref>}} This revelation touching on [[Cold War]] circumstances was subsequently analysed in greater detail in 2003 by ''[[Le Figaro Magazine|Le Figaro]]'' commentator {{Interlanguage link|R\u00e9mi Kauffer|fr}}.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kauffer, R\u00e9mi|title=Quand la CIA finan\u00e7ait la construction europ\u00e9enne - Par R\u00e9mi Kauffer, Source : Historia 2003|date=12 June 2019|url=http://www.comite-valmy.org/spip.php?article516|publisher=Comit\u00e9 Valmy|lang=fr|trans-title=When the CIA financed the construction of Europe by R\u00e9mi Kauffer, source: Historia 2003|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> However, as professor Hugh Wilford shows, the initiative to win American backing for a \"United States of Europe\" came neither from [[Allen Dulles]], deputy chief, then chief of the [[CIA]], nor from Senator [[William Fulbright]], chairman of the [[American Committee on United Europe]], but from European lobbyists of disparate motivation, namely Coudenhove-Kalergi and Retinger, the latter eclipsing the former due to Retinger's close connection with Winston Churchill on European matters.<ref name=\"wilford\"/> Retinger's plan was that the [[United States]] should be integral to political and economic support for a war-damaged [[Western Europe]]. As \"head of casting\" for his project, he set about finding key Americans to collaborate with him, among them [[Charles Douglas Jackson]], [[Time Inc.|Time-Life]] publisher in the 1940s and one-time head of propaganda at the [[Dwight D. Eisenhower|Eisenhower]] White House.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Bilderberg Conspiracy: Inside the World\u2019s Most Powerful Secret Society|author=Jeffers, H. Paul|chapter= 1|publisher= Kensington Publishing Corp.|date= 2012|isbn= 978-0-8065-3595-1}}</ref>\n\nRetinger has inspired disparate opinions. He was a figure whose allegiances, like his roots, remain obscure and whose accounts of himself varied according to his audience, thus undercutting his reliability \u2013 as reflected in various [[Joseph Conrad]] biographies and numerous other sources, including the considered, annotated review, by [[Norbert W\u00f3jtowicz]] of  Poland's [[Institute of National Remembrance]], of [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt|Marek Celt]]'s 2006 posthumously published ''Z Retingerem do Warszawy i z powrotem. Raport z podziemia 1944'', [''To Warsaw with Retinger and Back. A Report from the Underground 1944''] edited by Wojciech Frazik.<ref>{{cite web|author= Norbert W\u00f3jtowicz|title=Recenzja: Marek Celt, Z Retingerem do Warszawy i z powrotem. Raport z Podziemia 1944, red. Wojciech Frazik, Wydawnictwo LTW, \u0141omianki 2006 |trans-title = Review of Marek Celt, To Warsaw with Retinger and Back. A Report from the Underground 1944, ed. Wojciech Frazik pub. LTW. \u0141omianki, 2006|url=http://www.polska1918-89.pl/pdf/marek-celt,-z-retingerem-do-warszawy-i-z-powrotem.-raport-z-podziemia-,5423.pdf|publisher=www.polska1918-89|lang=pl|access-date=2020-03-31}} The book was subsequently translated into English by Jan Chciuk-Celt and published by McFarland in 2013 as ''Parachuting into Poland, 1944: Memoir of a Secret Mission with Jozef Retinger'', {{ISBN|978-1-4766-03384}} \"Marek Celt\", the pseudonym of Tadeusz Chciuk, was the military courier who accompanied Retinger on his parachute mission to Poland in 1944. A bond of friendship developed between the two men and they collaborated again on supplying aid to Warsaw from London in 1945-6.</ref> The disparity in views on Retinger, despite the perception of some personality flaws, does not alter Retinger's mature postwar European legacy.<ref>{{cite web|title= J\u00f3zef Retinger|publisher=bilderbergmeetings.co.uk|url= http://bilderbergmeetings.co.uk/jozef-retinger/|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n== Selected works==\nBy J. H. Retinger:\n* {{cite book|date= 1908|title=Le conte fantastique dans le romantisme fran\u00e7ais|place= Gen\u00e8ve|publisher= Slatkine Reprints, 1973|trans-title=Fantastical Tales in the French Romantic Tradition|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite book|title=Histoire de la litt\u00e9rature fran\u00e7aise du romantisme \u00e0 nos jours|place= Paris|publisher=[[\u00c9ditions Grasset| B. Grasset]]|date= 1911|trans-title=The History of French Literature from Romanticism to the Present Day|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite book|title= The Poles and Prussia|place=London|date=1913|url=https://explore.library.leeds.ac.uk/special-collections-explore/334918/the_poles_and_prussia?subject=%22Polish%20question%22&resultOffset=2}} available at University of Leeds Library\n* {{cite book|title=La Pologne et l'\u00c9quilibre europ\u00e9en|place= Paris|date= 1916|trans-title=Poland and the Stability of Europe|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite book|title=Morones of Mexico; a history of the labour movement in that country|place=London|publisher= The Labour Pub. Co. Ltd.|date= 1926}}\n* {{cite book|title=Tierra mexicana; the history of land and agriculture in ancient and modern Mexico|place= London|publisher= N. Douglas|date= 1928}}\n* {{cite book|title=Polacy w cywilizacjach zagranicznych|trans-title= Poles in Foreign Civilizations|place=Warsaw|date= 1934|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite journal|title= Historja i polityka: Nowy czynnik w dyplomacji mi\u0119dzynarodowej|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie (50)|date= 4 December 1938|trans-title=History and Politics: A new factor in international diplomacy|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite journal|title= Historja i polityka: Zast\u00f3j w mi\u0119dzynarodowej dzia\u0142alno\u015bci Rosji|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie (51)|date= 11 December 1938|trans-title=History and Politics: Suspension of Russian activity in international relations|lang=pl}} \n* {{cite book|title=All about Poland: facts, figures, documents|place= London|publisher= Minerva Pub. Co.|date= 1941}}\n* {{cite book|title=Conrad and His Contemporaries |year=1942 |publisher=Roy |location=New York|orig-year=First published by Minerva, London, 1941}}\n*  {{cite book|title= The European Continent? Address given to the Royal Institute of International Affairs in London|url=https://www.cvce.eu/content/publication/2008/2/19/534c684a-8924-445a-8181-58360f939f56/publishable_en.pdf|date= 7 May 1946|place=London}}\n*  {{cite book|title=The Bilderberg Group|place= Hertfordshire, UK|date= 1959}}\n*  {{cite book|title=Under Polish eyes|place=United Kingdom|publisher= Joseph Conrad Society|date= 1975}}\n\nAbout Retinger:\n* {{cite journal|author=Poraj, Stanis\u0142aw|title= The knight among nations|journal= Tydzie\u0144 Literacki Polski Zbrojnej, 2 (24)|lang=pl|date= 19 June 1938}}\n* {{cite book|author=[[Denis de Rougemont|de Rougemont, Denis]]|date= 1961|title=A Biographical Sketch. In Tribute to a Great European|editor= Retinger, J.H.|pages=20\u201350|place= Geneva|publisher= Centre Europe\u00e9n de la Culture|lang=}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Siemaszko, Zbigniew Sebastian|date=1967|title= Retinger w Polsce 1944 r.|place=Paris|journal= Zeszyty Historyczne, 12|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|title=J\u00f3zef Retinger: Memoirs of an Eminence Grise|editor=Pomian, John|publisher= Sussex University Press/Chatto & Windus|date= 1972| isbn=0-85621-002-1|oclc=844436367}}.\n* {{cite book|author=[[Jan Nowak-Jeziora\u0144ski|Nowak, Jan]]|title= Kurier z Warszawy|place= London|publisher= Odnowa|date= 1978|lang=pl|isbn= 0-903705-37-0}}\n* {{cite book|publisher=[[Polski S\u0142ownik Biograficzny]]|title= J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|volume= XXXI|date= 1988-1989|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|title=In remembrance of Joseph Retinger 1988-1960, Initiator of the European League for Economic Cooperation|publisher= [[European League for Economic Cooperation]]|place= Brussels|date= 1996}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Grosbois, Thierry|date= 1999|title=L'action de J\u00f3zef Retinger en faveur de l'id\u00e9e europ\u00e9enne 1940-46|journal= Revue Europ\u00e9enne d'Histoire| volume= 6|issue= 34|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Kalicki, W\u0142odzimierz|date=2010|title=Gracz, kt\u00f3ry budowa\u0142 Europ\u0119|trans-title=The Player who built Europe|journal= Gazeta Wyborcza |issue=219|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|authors=\t[[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt|Marek Celt]], Jan Chciuk-Celt|title=Parachuting into Poland, 1944: Memoir of a Secret Mission with Jozef Retinger|publisher=McFarland|date= 2013|isbn=978-1-4766-03384}}\n* {{cite book|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|title= J\u00f3zef Retinger \u2013 prywatny polityk|trans-title=J\u00f3zef Retinger - a private politician|publisher= Universitas|date= 2013|lang=pl|isbn=97883-242-2351-0}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of governments in exile during World War II]]\n*[[European Movement]]\n*[[European Union]]\n*[[List of Poles#Diplomats|List of Poles]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal|author=Pragier, Adam|title=Nie by\u0142o k\u0142opotu z Polakami|trans-title=There was no Problem with the Poles|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci, Rok 10, Nr 21 (477)|lang=pl|date=1955-05-22|place=London|url=http://retropress.pl/wiadomosci/nie-bylo-klopotu-z-polakami/}}\n* {{cite book|author=Bines, Jeffrey|title=Poland's S.O.E: A British Perspective: the Story of the Polish Country Section of the Special Operations Executive 1940-1946 Including the British Military Mission Number Four to Poland 1939|publisher=Polish Underground Movement Study Trust|date= 2018|place=London|isbn=978-0-9928-03056}} \n* {{cite journal|author= Biskupski, M.B.|title=Spy, Patriot or Internationalist? The Early Career of J\u00f3zef Retinger, Polish Patriarch of European Union|journal=[[The Polish Review]]| volume= 43|date= 1998|issue=1| pages= 23\u201367}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Bu\u0142hak, W\u0142adys\u0142aw|title=The Foreign Office and the Special Operations Executive and the Expedition of J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger to Poland, April\u2013July 1944|journal=The Polish Review| volume= 61|date= 2016|issue=3| pages= 33\u201357|doi=10.5406/polishreview.61.3.0033}}\n* {{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=J\u00f3zef H. Retinger \u2013 pomys\u0142odawca i wsp\u00f3\u0142tw\u00f3rca Grupy Bilderbergu|trans-title=Joseph Retinger: Visionary Co-founder of the [[Bilderberg Group]]|lang=pl|journal= Studia polityczne|publisher= ISP PAN|volume= 10|date= 2000}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Dzia\u0142alno\u015b\u0107 J.H. Retingera na rzecz zjednoczonej Europy|trans-title=Joseph Retinger\u2019s Work for a United Europe|journal= Studia Europejskie|publisher= Centrum Europejskie Uniwersytetu Warszawskiego|volume=  16|date= 2000|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Dzia\u0142alno\u015b\u0107 J\u00f3zefa Hieronima Retingera na rzecz integracji europejskiej|lang=pl|trans-title= Joseph Retinger\u2019s Work for European Integration|publisher= Wydawnictwo Adam Marsza\u0142ek|place= Toru\u0144|date= 2008|isbn=978-83-7611-184-1}}\n* {{cite book|author= Hampson, Robert|title=Conrad's Secrets|publisher=\tPalgrave Macmillan|date= 2012|isbn=978-0-2305-0783-8}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Joseph Retinger's Vision of [a] United Europe After World War II: Central and Eastern European Question|journal= [[The Polish Review]]| volume= 60|date= 2015 |issue=4|pages= 49\u201366|doi=10.5406/polishreview.60.4.0049}}\n* {{cite book|author=Wisnewski, Gerhard|title=The Bilderbergers Puppet-Masters of Power?: An Investigation into Claims of Conspiracy at the Heart of Politics, Business and the Media|translator=J. Collis|trans-title=Drahtzieher der Macht (2010)|date=2014|place=West Sussex|publisher=Clairview Books|isbn=978-1-90557075-1|pages=63\u201366}}\n* {{cite book|title=Informal Alliance: The Bilderberg Group and Transatlantic Relations during the Cold War, 1952-1968|series=  Routledge Studies in Modern History|author=Gijswijt, Thomas W.|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date= 2018|isbn=978-1-3511-8102-0}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20161027232624/http://home.teleport.com/~flyheart/retinger.htm Illustrated biography of Jozef Retinger assembled by Jan Chciuk-Celt]\n*[https://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/205254911 Polish Soviet Relations During The Second World War, photographs held by the [[Imperial War Museum]] with J\u00f3zef Retinger (extreme left) at the signing of the Sikorski-Maiski agreement at the FO on 30.07.1941]\n*[http://www.jasperfforde.com/ten_things/ten_things8.html Photograph of Retinger flanking Churchill at the Hague 1948, on Retinger's grandson's website]\n*[http://www.bilderberg.org/bildhist.htm#Memoirs Chapter 4, European Unity, from ''Memoirs of An Eminence Grise'' ed. John Pomian]\n*[http://bilderbergmeetings.co.uk/jozef-retinger/ Bilderberg website on Retinger's life in brief]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Retinger, Jozef}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Poland to Russia]]\n[[Category:Council of Europe]]\n[[Category:Members of the Steering Committee of the Bilderberg Group]]\n[[Category:Polish politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Freemasons]]\n[[Category:European integration pioneers]]\n[[Category:Geopoliticians]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Polish diplomats]]\n[[Category:Polish spies]]\n[[Category:Secret Intelligence Service personnel]]\n[[Category:Special Operations Executive personnel]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish writers]]\n[[Category:Exophonic writers]]\n[[Category:Polish essayists]]\n[[Category:Male essayists]]\n[[Category:Polish political writers]]\n[[Category:Polish people of World War II]]\n[[Category:People of World War II]]\n[[Category:History of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Rusyn descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Polish diplomat and activist}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger\n|image             = File:Jozef Retinger.jpg\n|image_size        = \n|caption           = J\u00f3zef Retinger, recovering from a poisoning attempt c.1944<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n|birth_date        = {{birth date|1888|04|17|df=y}}\n|birth_place       = [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]]\n|death_date        = {{death date and age|df=yes|1960|06|12|1888|04|17}}\n|death_place       = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n|citizenship       = Polish\n|nationality       = Polish\n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = Economics, international relations, politics\n|work_institutions = [[Sorbonne University]] Phd, [[London School of Economics]], [[Polish government-in-exile]]\n|doctoral_advisor  =\n|doctoral_students =\n|known_for         = [[Bilderberg Group]], [[European Movement International]]\n|author_abbrev_bot =\n|author_abbrev_zoo =\n|influences        = [[Jesuits]], [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]]\n|influenced        = [[Joseph Conrad]], foundation of [[European Union]], the [[Bilderberg Group]]\n|prizes            = [[Nobel Peace Prize]] Nomination 1958\n|footnotes         =\n|signature         =\n}}\n'''J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger''' ([[Krak\u00f3w]], 17 April 1888 {{spaced ndash}} 12 June 1960, [[London]]; [[World War II]] [[nom de guerre|noms de guerre]] ''Salamandra'', \"Salamander\", and ''Brzoza'', \"Birch Tree\") was a [[Poles|Polish]] scholar, international political activist with access to some of the leading power brokers of the 20th century, a publicist and writer.\n\nAlready as a gifted student in [[Paris]] and [[London]] he mixed with the leading lights of music and literature. Most notably, he became a friend of compatriot [[Joseph Conrad]].<ref name = \"JR\">{{cite book|title=Joseph Retinger - Memoirs of an Eminence Grise|editor=John Pomian|publisher=Sussex University Press/ Chatto & Windus|date= 1972|url=https://ia800905.us.archive.org/5/items/MemoirsOfAnEminenceGrise1972/Memoirs%20of%20an%20Eminence%20Grise%2C%201972.pdf}}</ref> During [[World War I]], the young Retinger became politically active in [[Austria-Hungary]] and [[Russian Empire|Russia]] on behalf of the Polish independence movement. Following a failed attempt to broker peace between Austria-Hungary and the [[Allies of World War I]], he had to retreat to [[Central America]], where he became an economic adviser.\n\nAfter the outbreak of [[World War II]], he was principal adviser to the [[Polish government-in-exile]]. Early in 1944, a daring mission into [[Occupied Poland]] by parachute, with the help of British intelligence, added to his air of mystery and subsequent controversy.<ref name=\"Oleks\">{{cite web|title=The Most Mysterious Man in 20th-Century Politics|author=Oleksiak, Wojciech|publisher=Culture.pl|date=2016-12-14|url=https://culture.pl/en/article/the-most-mysterious-man-in-20th-century-politics|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> A Freemason with a reputation as a [[grey eminence]], after World War II he went on to cofound the [[European Movement]], which led to establishment of the [[European Union]], and was instrumental in forming the secretive [[Bilderberg Group]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pieczewski|first1=Andrzej|title=Joseph Retinger's conception of and contribution to the early process of European integration|journal=European Review of History|date=11 Aug 2010|volume=17|issue=4|pages=581\u2013604|doi=10.1080/13507486.2010.495766}}</ref> In 1958 he was nominated for the [[Nobel Peace Prize]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Emilian Czyrnia\u0144ski.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Emilian Czyrnia\u0144ski]], Retinger's maternal grandfather, 1878 photo by [[Walery Rzewuski]]]]\n[[File:Wierchy-1925---W\u0142adys\u0142aw-Zamoyski-(1853-1924).png|thumb|150px|[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]] (1853-1924)]]\n[[File:Misa Sert.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Misia Sert|Misia Godebska Sert]], Retinger's Parisian cousin]]\nJ\u00f3zef Retinger was born in [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Poland]] (then part of [[Austria-Hungary]]), the youngest of five children: his father had a daughter, Aniela, from a first marriage to Helena Jawornicka.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\">{{cite web|title=J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|url=https://kangur.uek.krakow.pl//biblioteka/retinger/B.%20Podgorski%20-%20J.H.%20Retinger%201888-1960.pdf|lang=pl|page=5|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> His mother was Maria Krystyna [[Emil Czyrnia\u0144ski|Czyrnia\u0144ska]], daughter of a [[Greek Catholic Church|Greek Catholic]] [[Lemkos|Lemko]] professor of chemistry at the [[Jagiellonian University]]. His father, J\u00f3zef Stanis\u0142aw Retinger, was the personal legal counsel and successful adviser to French-born Count [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]]. Retinger's great grandfather, Filip Rettinger, was a Jewish tailor from [[Tarn\u00f3w]] who with his family converted to Catholicism in 1827.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Sypek, Antoni|title=\u017bydowskie konwersje na chrze\u015bcija\u0144stwo w Tarnowie, w latach 1785-1900|journal= Rocznik Tarnowski|date= 2013| page= 128|trans-title= Jewish conversions to christianity in Tarn\u00f3w in 1785-1900}}</ref> When his lawyer grandson died, Count Zamoyski took the promising youngster, J\u00f3zef, into his household and paid for him to attend the [[Bart\u0142omiej Nowodworski High School]] in Krak\u00f3w. Retinger's eldest brother, Emil, became a commander in the [[Polish Navy]], while his son, {{Interlanguage link|Witold Retinger|pl}}, was stationed in the [[United Kingdom]] during [[World War II]] (1943\u201345), as a member then leader of [[No. 308 Polish Fighter Squadron|Squadron 308]] of the [[Polish Air Forces in France and Great Britain|Polish Air Force]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafweb.org/Squadrons/Sqn300-318.htm|title=History of No.'s 300\u2013318 Squadrons at RAF Web|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Retinger's brother, Juliusz, taught [[physiological chemistry]] at the [[University of Chicago]] and [[University of Wilno]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Polish Biographical Dictionary|title-link= Polish Biographical Dictionary|volume= 127|page= 152|lang=pl}}</ref> Retinger himself initially considered a career in the priesthood, but three months in the Jesuit [[novitiate]] in [[Rome]] confirmed he would not be suited to the life.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n\nFurther financed by Count Zamoyski in 1906, Retinger entered simultaneously the [[Ecole des sciences politiques]] and the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]] in [[Paris]] and two years later, aged twenty, became the youngest person ever to earn a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in literature from there.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> While in the French capital, armed with introductions from Zamoyski and his own relative, the salonni\u00e8re and pianist [[Misia Sert]], he moved in intellectual circles and was befriended by among others, [[Andr\u00e9 Gide]], [[Fran\u00e7ois Mauriac]], {{ill|Bernard Grasset (publisher)|lt=Bernard Grasset|fr|Bernard Grasset (\u00e9diteur)}}, [[Jean Giraudoux]], [[Erik Satie]] and [[Maurice Ravel]]. His early literary ambitions were stopped in their tracks when he presented his first novel, ''\"Les Souffleurs\"'' to Andr\u00e9 Gide for his opinion. Gide told him: ''Joseph, you will never be a writer.''<ref name = \"JR\"/>{{rp|pages=11\u201313}}\n\nHe next went to [[Munich]] to study [[comparative psychology]] for a year. From there, encouraged by Zamoyski, in 1910 he moved to [[England]], where he entered the [[London School of Economics]] for a year's study and began a lobbying operation on behalf of the Polish cause and its populations scattered across three ailing empires. Formally he became Director of the London Office of the Polish National Committee (1912\u20131914).<ref>{{cite web|title=Jozef Retinger - cv|url=https://www.cvce.eu/en/obj/joseph_retinger-en-9d454c22-957c-49ef-8c7b-be5f98d676fc.htmlE|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|first1=Wojciech|last1=Roszkowski|first2=Jan|last2=Kofman|title=Biographical Dictionary of Central and Eastern Europe in the Twentieth Century|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date=2016|isbn=9781317475934|chapter-url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=RnKlDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA2377|access-date=2017-07-25|chapter=Retinger J\u00f3zef}}</ref> During this time he continued to move in \u00e9lite circles and  thanks to an introduction by [[Arnold Bennett]] whom he had met in Paris, Retinger developed a close friendship with his older Polish compatriot, the already well established novelist, [[Joseph Conrad]].<ref name=\":0\"/> Retinger urged Conrad to visit Poland, and on 28 July 1914, the day [[World War I]] broke out, Retinger, his wife Otolia, and Conrad, his wife, and their two sons arrived in Krak\u00f3w, the two men's childhood stamping grounds (they were alumni of the same [[secondary school]]). Due to the closeness of the Russian border (Russia was then allied to Great Britain), the Conrads soon sought greater safety in the [[Tatra Mountains]] resort of [[Zakopane]].<ref>[[Zdzis\u0142aw Najder]], ''Joseph Conrad: A Life'', Rochester, New York, Camden House, 2007, {{ISBN|978-1-57113-347-2}}, pp. 459\u201363.</ref> Retinger would write about Conrad in his 1943 book, ''Conrad and His Contemporaries''. Historian [[Norman Davies]] suggests that it was probably Conrad who introduced the \"polyglot and polymath\" Retinger to the British intelligence services.<ref name=\"Davies\">{{cite book|author=Davies, Norman|title=Rising '44: The Battle for Warsaw|title-link=Rising '44|year=2003|place= London|publisher= Pan Books|isbn=0-333-90568-7| page= 53}}</ref> Later Retinger became a personal friend of Major-General Sir [[Colin Gubbins]], wartime head of [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]], and after the war an [[Special Intelligence Service|MI6]] \"asset\".<ref name=\"wilford\">{{cite book|title=The CIA, the British Left and the Cold War: Calling the Tune? Studies in Intelligence|author= Wilford, Hugh|publisher=Routledge|date= 2013|page=242|isbn=978-1135294779}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Dorril, Stephen|title= A Critical Review: MI6: Fifty years of special operations. Doctoral thesis|publisher= University of Huddersfield|date=2010|url=http://eprints.hud.ac.uk/id/eprint/9763/1/sdorrilfinalthesis.pdf|page=27}}</ref>\n\n===World War I===\n[[File:Joseph Conrad author.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Joseph Conrad]]]]\nWith the clouds of war closing in, the project of writing a play together with Conrad based on the latter's novel, ''[[Nostromo]]'' had to be abandoned as both men hurriedly left Austria Hungary. Retinger would have been eligible for military call up in [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]], but no mention of this is made by his biographers. Instead, he put aside literary endeavours and once more assumed the role of a political lobbyist for Poland, publishing pamphlets and travelling between London, Paris and [[New York City|New York]], aided by Conrad in London.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=10}} In the first years of the war, this was not on the agenda of the major powers. Retinger looked instead for other potential alliances and political leverage which led to meetings with leading [[Zionism|Zionists]] of the time, including [[Chaim Weizmann]], [[Vladimir Zhabotinski]] and [[Nahum Sokolow]] who were seeking international recognition and rights for the [[Jewish diaspora]].<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=11}} In 1916 guided by Zamoyski and with the approval of [[Herbert Asquith]], [[David Lloyd George]] and [[Georges Clemenceau]] with his old Parisian connections, [[Prince Sixtus of Bourbon-Parma|Sixtus]] and [[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Xavier de Bourbon Parme]], the Duchess of Montebello and Marquis [[Boni de Castellane]], as well as Zamoyski's friend the Polish [[General of the Jesuits]], [[Wlodimir Led\u00f3chowski|W\u0142odzimierz Led\u00f3chowski]], Retinger became a \"courier\" in the secretive European dynastic negotiation suing for peace with Austria.<ref name= \"Kultura\">{{cite journal|author=Jele\u0144ski, K.A.|title=Prekursor anachroniczny|journal=[[Kultura|Kultura Paryska]]|location=Paris|date=1961|lang=pl|trans-title= Anachronistic Precursor (Obituary)|pages=190\u2013193|url=http://static.kulturaparyska.com/attachments/51/96/79311ebf90d26ec65a78e3b802589c43f76cb880.pdf#page=97}}</ref> It became known as the ''[[Sixtus Affair]]'' but was a failure, due to Germany's refusal to cooperate thus making Austria more dependent on it.<ref>{{cite book|title=Informal Alliance: The Bilderberg Group and Transatlantic Relations during the Cold War, 1952-1968|series=  Routledge Studies in Modern History|author=Gijswijt, Thomas W.|chapter=J\u00f3zef Retinger - Informal diplomat|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date= 2018|isbn=978-1-3511-8102-0}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1 = Demblin, August | author2 = Demblin, Alexander | title = Minister gegen Kaiser : Aufzeichnungen eines \u00f6sterreichisch-ungarischen Diplomaten \u00fcber Aussenminister Czernin und Kaiser Karl |lang= de| date = 1997 | publisher = B\u00f6hlau | place = Vienna | isbn = 3-205-98762-4 | trans-title=Minister versus Kaiser: The designs of an Austro-Hungarian Diplomat to outwit Foreign Minister Czernin and [[Charles I of Austria|Kaiser Charles]]}}</ref> In 1917 he met [[Boy Capel|Arthur \"Boy\" Capel]], the half-French dilettante, polo player and \"sponsor\" of [[Coco Chanel]]. Capel is said to have planted in Retinger's mind the idea of a world federal government based on an Anglo-French alliance.<ref>{{cite journal|author= Biskupski, M. B.|title= Spy, Patriot or Internationalist? The Early Career of J\u00f3zef Retinger, Polish Patriarch of the European Union|journal= The Polish Review, Vol. 43, No. 1|date= 1998|pages= 23\u201367}}</ref> After concerns for his personal safety due to his \"political meddling\" in Austria-Hungary and in the emergent [[Soviet Union]], in 1918 Retinger was banned from France, and sought sanctuary in [[Spain]] for several months.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=12}}\n\n==Mexican years==\n[[File:Jane Anderson 1917.JPG|thumb|left|150px|US journalist [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]] 1917]] \nHe travelled on to [[Cuba]] and then to [[Mexico]], where he became an unofficial political adviser to union organizer [[Luis Morones]] whom he fortuitously met crossing the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]], and to President [[Plutarco El\u00edas Calles]].<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/><ref name=\"Oleks\"/> A glimpse of Retinger, newly divorced and love lorn for the American journalist, [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]], appears in the biography of another American woman, the communist sympathiser [[Katherine Anne Porter]], a member of the Morones circle. In it he is described as a \"Polish intriguer\" and \"British Marxist\". In 1921 while on an obscure mission to the [[United States]] to buy saddles, Retinger was arrested and imprisoned in [[Laredo, Texas|Laredo]] and Porter was despatched from Mexico to get him released.<ref name= \"Stout\">{{cite book|title=Katherine Anne Porter: A Sense of the Times - Minds of the new South|author=Stout, Janis P.|publisher=University of Virginia Press|date= 1995|pages=47\u201351|isbn= 978-0-813915685}}</ref> That same year Retinger had proposed that Katherine Porter and her friend Mary Doherty accompany him to Europe to do \"collaborative work\", an offer that was spurned.<ref name= \"Stout\"/>{{rp|pages=94\u201395}} Retinger helped advance Mexico's nationalization of its oil industry in 1928.<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\">{{cite journal|author=Ethridge, Marcus E.|title= Review of M.B.B. Biskupski, \"War and Diplomacy in East and West: A Biography of J\u00f3zef Retinger\", London, Routledge, 2017, ISBN: 978-1-138-21845-1|journal= [[The Polish Review]]| volume= 64|date= 2019|issue= 1| page= 95|doi= 10.5406/polishreview.64.1.0094}} Ethridge's full review is on pp. 94\u201395</ref> His activities in Mexico lasted a total of almost seven years and only ended with Calles's fall from power in 1936. They inspired Retinger to write three volumes on the tumultuous events of that Latin American republic.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/> The Mexican years were punctuated by trips back to Europe where he took on the role of Representative in the United Kingdom of the Polish Socialist Party (1924\u20131928). In 1926 he married his second wife, Stella, with whom he travelled to Mexico on one occasion. After her death in 1933 his two daughters were left in the care of their maternal grandmother and were estranged from him until the 1950s.\n\nIn the rest of the interwar period, he published many contributions in periodicals, such as the Polish ''Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie'' (Literary News) (see [[Wiadomo\u015bci (London magazine)|Wiadomo\u015bci]]), on literary and political subjects.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/><ref>{{cite journal|title=Hitleryzm czyli bolszewizm|author=Retinger, J.H.|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie|date=1939-03-12|url=http://retropress.pl/wiadomosci-literackie/hitleryzm-czyli-bolszewizm/|issue=11 (803), year 16|lang=pl|trans-title=Hitlerism equals Bolshevism}}</ref>\n\n==Building blocks on the table==\n[[File:W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski, 1923.jpg|thumb|150px|[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]], Polish prime minister in 1923]]\nDuring [[World War II]], Retinger who was in [[London]], was involved in arranging for Polish troops to be transferred to Britain from France. He was bidden by Winston Churchill personally to escort [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]] by plane to England from France which had just capitulated to the invading Germans.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=16}} He became principal adviser and confidant to the Prime Minister of the [[Polish Government in Exile]] now re-established in London.<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>{{rp|page= 95}}<ref>{{cite web|title=London Gazette|date=1942-12-04|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/35811/page/5301/data.pdf|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> In fact, their political relationship went back to 1916 and was strengthened during [[Wladyslaw Sikorski]]'s earlier brief stint as prime minister, 1922-23 in newly independent Poland, and came to greater fruition when both men were later in exile in London.<ref name=\"Lane\">{{cite book|title=Poland and European Integration: The Ideas and Movements of Polish Exiles in the West, 1939\u201391|author1=Lane, Thomas |author2=Wolanski, Marian|publisher=Springer|date= 2009|page=18|isbn=978-0-2302-71784}}</ref>\n\nSikorski's dependence on Retinger was the greater as he did not have mastery of [[English language|English]]. At this time Retinger was despatched to talk with other exiled government representatives in London, who included [[Marcel-Henri Jaspar]], [[Paul Van Zeeland]], [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] in preparation for a post-war geopolitical landscape.<ref>{{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1|page=455}}</ref> He went on to posit a \"Sikorski Plan\" consisting of two stages, the first of which was signed in January 1942 and proposed a Polish-Czech confederation.<ref>{{cite book|author=Walter Lipgens|title=Documents on the history of European integration: Plans for European union in Great Britain and in exile, 1939\u20131945 (including 107 documents in their original languages on 3 microfiches)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X3TsVCAt9F4C&pg=PA648|accessdate=10 August 2011|year=1985|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-009724-5|page=648}}</ref> The idea was to expand it into a [[wikt:Central Europe|Central Europe]]an confederation with Poland and [[Lithuania]], [[Czechoslovakia]] as its nucleus around which would be grouped [[Romania]], [[Hungary]], Yugoslavia and [[Greece]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Schmidt, Andrea|title=From Intermarium to the Three Seas Initiative: The Implications of the Polish Orientation Over the Central and Eastern European Region on Hungarian Policy in Baltic-Black Sea Regionalisms: Patchworks and Networks at Europe's Eastern Margins|editor1=Bogdanova, Olga |editor2=Makarychev, Andrey|publisher=Springer Nature|date= 2019|page=157|isbn= 978-3-0302-48789}}</ref> The agenda behind this was to create a common political blue-print for smaller countries abutting larger European powers and became the basis of a Belgian-Dutch union which would mirror the Polish-Czech arrangement.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Together and Alone in Allied London: Czechoslovak, Norwegian and Polish Governments-in-Exile, 1940\u20131945|author=Jakubec, Pavol|journal=[[International History Review]]|date=2019|doi=10.1080/07075332.2019.1600156|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nThis scheme of Retinger's caused problems between London and [[Moscow]]. In order not to tread on Soviet toes, the British altered their position and refused to back Sikorski's negotiations with the eight smaller European states. In his speech on the Council of Europe, [[Winston Churchill]] [https://www.winstonchurchill.org/resources/speeches/1941-1945-war-leader/national-address/ BBC radio broadcast] on 21 March 1943 referred to the necessity of smaller nations forming groupings, but that it was too early to go into detail. The most Retinger was able to achieve was to push through the [[Sikorski-Mayski Agreement]], signed on 30 July 1941, which provided for the formation of the [[Anders' army]], thus ridding Stalin of the immediate human problem posed by the hundreds of thousands of Polish [[Prisoner of war|POW]]s and deportees from the [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u201345)|Soviet occupied]] [[Kresy Zachodnie|Kresy]] regions of the former [[Second Polish Republic]], who after an arduous odyssey across thousands of miles would eventually end up as the [[United Kingdom]]'s human problem.<ref>{{cite book|author=Anders, Lt.-General W\u0142adys\u0142aw|title= An Army in Exile|publisher= MacMillan & Co. Ltd|date=1949|page=73}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Polish Underground Army, the Western Allies, and the Failure of Strategic Unity in World War II|author=Peszke, Michael Alfred|publisher=McFarland|date= 2015|isbn=978-1-4766-10276|page=70}}</ref> This trade-off adumbrated the [[Tehran Conference|Tehran]] and [[Yalta Conference]]s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Identity in Flux. The Polish Community in Britain|author=Sword, Keith|place=London|publisher=School of Slavonic and East European Studies - SSEES Occasional Papers No. 36| date=1996|isbn=0-903425-60-2|pages=24\u201330|url=https://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/id/eprint/10078280/1/SSEES0012.pdf|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Brushes with death==\nRetinger narrowly avoided perishing in the sea off [[Gibraltar]] with [[Wladyslaw Sikorski's death controversy|W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]], in July 1943, but for the fact that he was not needed to accompany the premier on a troop inspection in the Middle East and would be better employed in London. The spare seat on the plane went to Sikorski's daughter who died with her father.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> Retinger was devastated by this turn of events. His relationship with Sikorski's successor, [[Stanislaw Mikolajczyk]] was much more ambivalent, but he obtained his consent for a special mission to Poland under [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]] in April 1944.<ref>Bu\u0142hak, W\u0142adys\u0142aw. \"The Foreign Office and the [[Special Operations Executive]] and the Expedition of J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger to Poland, April\u2013July 1944\", ''[[The Polish Review]]'', vol. 61, no. 3, 2016, pp. 33\u201357.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Members of the Polish Government, Prime Minister's Office|publisher=the Gazette|location=Edinburgh|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/Edinburgh/issue/16118/page/134/data.pdf|page=184|date=1944-04-21|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nWith an SOE brief and without prior training, Retinger, aged 56, parachuted into [[German-occupied Poland|occupied Poland]] with 2nd Lt. [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt]], (see [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt#Operation \"Salamander\"|Operation Salamander]]), to meet with Polish underground figures, to deliver money to the Polish underground, and to \"explain to his fellow Poles in the homeland 'how are we going to lose this war'\".<ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\">{{cite book|last1=Eringer|first1=Robert|author-link=Robert Eringer|title=The Global Manipulators|publisher=Pentacle Books|asin=B00546KTEM|oclc=26551991}}</ref>{{rp|pages=16\u201322}} <ref name = \"JR\"/>{{rp|page=265}}<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>  Following at least one assassination attempt on him, Retinger expressed his frustration thus:\n\n{{blockquote|You know why I came.  The [Underground] [[Government Delegation for Poland|Delegate]] knows as well.... They know that I only want to convince them that it will be necessary in the future to cooperate with the Communists, because no English are coming here, only Russians.  If we do not get along with them somehow, it will be a terrible tragedy, because we well know what [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]] and the [[NKVD]] [Interior Ministry of the Soviet Union] are. And it's about trying to make people here understand this fact. And they want to murder me!}}<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>\n\nThe latter quip was a reference to elements in the [[Polish Underground Army]], the [[Armia Krajowa|AK]] who were convinced Retinger was not serving the interests of his country and should therefore be \"removed\". One apparent attempt to liquidate him in Poland was on the grounds of a \"death sentence\" to be carried out on the alleged orders of general [[Kazimierz Sosnkowski]]. It was foiled by the intervention of an old friend and [[Armia Krajowa|AK fighter]], Tadeusz Gebethner.<ref>{{cite web|title=The story of Tadeusz Gebethner|url=https://sprawiedliwi.org.pl/en/stories-of-rescue/story-tadeusz-gebethner|publisher=sprawiedliwi.org.pl |access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> There was also an attempt during his visit in occupied Poland to poison him, which failed. On his return to London, he spent some time in the [[Dorchester Hotel]] in London's [[Park Lane, London|Park Lane]] recovering from his ordeal of the trip, which left him lame in one leg for the rest of his life, possibly due to the [[Polyneuritis]] brought on by the poison. His first visitor at the Dorchester was Sir [[Anthony Eden]], the foreign secretary.<ref name=\"Davies\"/><ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\"/>\n\nImmediately after the war, in 1945-6 Retinger travelled to [[Warsaw]] with emergency aid for the capital's population. It consisted largely of tons of British and US Army surplus, such as equipment, blankets and field-kitchens.<ref name= \"Kultura\"/> When his erstwhile military escort from \"operation Salamander\", [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt|Tadeusz Chciuk]] and his new wife, Ewa, were arrested in Poland as subversives by the Polish Communist security service, Retinger allegedly appealed over their heads directly to [[Vyacheslav Molotov|Molotov]] in [[Moscow]] to have them released. Apparently the personal intervention succeeded. In 1948 the Chciuks became refugees in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jozef Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Chciuk-Celt, Jan|url=http://pdf.amazingdiscoveries.org/References/RB/275%20PDFs/jozef-hieronim-retinger-slide-79.pdf|access-date=2020-03-03}} Jan Chciuk-Celt is the younger son of Tadeusz Chciuk, Retinger's military courier during \"Operation Saamander\" and was a co-author and editor of his father's war memoirs.</ref><ref>{{cite book|authors=[[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt|Marek Celt]], Jan Chciuk-Celt|title=Parachuting into Poland, 1944: Memoir of a Secret Mission with Jozef Retinger|publisher=McFarland|page=17|date= 2013|isbn=978-1-4766-03384}}</ref>\n\n===Unwanted intrusion===\nDark days followed World War II when tensions rose between former Western and Eastern allies and in April 1946 Retinger's flat in [[Bayswater]], West London, was broken into and his and his secretary's files ransacked by persons unknown. He reported the matter to [[Scotland Yard]], but the [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]] were not overly bothered. As a result, Retinger escalated his complaint and ended up being interviewed by the Britain's security services. His view was that the newly communist embassy of the [[Polish People's Republic]] were responsible for the break-in.<ref>{{cite book|author=Moss, Eloise|title=Night Raiders: Burglary and the Making of Modern Urban Life in London, 1860-1968|publisher=Oxford University Press|date= 2019|pages=186\u201387|isbn=978-0-1925-7677-4}}</ref>\n\nFrom the moment Winston Churchill had made his \"[[Iron Curtain]]\" speech in [[Fulton, Missouri]], in April 1946, Retinger turned his efforts to a modified European project he had harboured for decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.winstonchurchill.org/i4a/pages/index.cfm?pageid=429 |title=Sinews of Peace (Iron Curtain) |accessdate=2007-02-26 |last=Churchill |first=Winston |publisher=Churchill Centre |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070207054810/http://www.winstonchurchill.org/i4a/pages/index.cfm?pageid=429 |archivedate=7 February 2007 }}</ref><ref name= \"Kultura\"/>\n\n==Vision for Europe==\n[[File:Krakow-Jozef Retinger plaque.jpg|thumb|right|[[Krak\u00f3w]] plaque commemorating Retinger, \"great pioneer of European unity\".]]\nAfter World War II, Retinger feared another devastating war in Europe, this time fought between \"Russia\" and \"the Anglo-Saxons\".<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/> He became a leading advocate of [[European unification]] as a means of securing peace.<ref>{{cite web|author=Retinger, J. H.|title= The European Continent? Address given to the Royal Institute of Foreign Affairs in London|url=https://www.cvce.eu/content/publication/2008/2/19/534c684a-8924-445a-8181-58360f939f56/publishable_en.pdf|publisher=CVCE|date= 7 May 1946|access-date=2020-03-27}} Correction: although the original states Royal Institute of Foreign Affairs, it should read [[Royal Institute of International Affairs]], known today as \"[[Chatham House]]\", this is likely a copyediting error at CVCE (ed.).</ref> He helped found both the [[European Movement]] and the [[Council of Europe]], somewhat to the dismay of the philosopher Count [[Richard Coudenhove-Kalergi]], the post-[[World War I]] [[Anti-communism|anti-bolshevist]] founder of the [[Paneuropean Union]] movement.<ref name=\"wilford\"/>{{rp|pages=227\u2013228}}<ref>{{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1|page=165}}</ref>\n\nRetinger, with his connections in Holland, Belgium, and [[Switzerland]] (he was a friend of [[Denis de Rougemont]]), took his cue from [[Winston Churchill]]'s 1947 [[Zurich]] speech and found fertile ground with thirteen British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] members of Parliament who backed the idea of a loose European association of states. Working in particular with Britain's [[Duncan Sandys]], incidentally Churchill's son-in-law, he took on the lion's share of the work and became Honorary Secretary General of the [[European Movement]]. He organised the 1948 [[Congress of Europe|Hague Congress]] which brought together the two camps of those for a unified Europe and those in favour of a federal Europe.<ref name=\"Lane\"/> During the congress, Retinger networked assiduously among the delegates, who included the Vatican diplomat, [[Giovanni Montini]], the future [[Pope Paul VI]]. Ensuing discussions led eventually to the formation in 1951 of a [[European Coal and Steel Community]].<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n\n===Creator of Bilderberg===\nRetinger was the initiator and architect of the informal [[Bilderberg Group|Bilderberg]] conferences in 1952-54 and was their permanent secretary until his premature death in London in 1960. The original group which met in the eponymous Dutch hotel in 1954 was gathered by  Retinger and included [[David Rockefeller]], [[Denis Healey]] with [[Prince Bernhard of Lippe-Biesterfeld|Prince Bernhard of the Netherlands]], (a former SS officer), as chairman. The purpose was to stimulate understanding between Europe and the US as the Cold War developed by bringing together financiers, industrialists, politicians and opinion formers. All discussions were to be strictly under [[Chatham House Rule]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Bunting, Madeleine|title=Weekend break for the global elite|journal=[[The Guardian]]|date=2001-05-25}}</ref> A founding member of the group, later British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Foreign Secretary, Healey, described the secretive Bilderberg meetings as the \"brainchild\" of Retinger.<ref>{{cite web|title=Denis Healey on Bilderberg|url=https://www.worldsocialism.org/spgb/socialist-standard/2002/2000s/no-1175-july-2002/denis-healey-bilderberg/|publisher=worldsocialism.org|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Aubourg, Valerie|title=Organizing Atlanticism: the Bilderberg group and the Atlantic institute, 1952\u20131963|journal=[[Intelligence and National Security]]|volume=18, (2)|date=2003|pages= 92\u2013105 |doi=10.1080/02684520412331306760}}</ref>\n\nDespite eschewing any distinctions or medals throughout his life, in 1958 he was nominated for the Nobel Peace Prize.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.nobelprize.org/nomination/archive/show.php?id=15660 |title =Nomination for Nobel Peace Prize: Joseph Retinger |author =Nobelprize.org |publisher =Nobel Media AB 2014 |website = Nomination Database| date = |access-date = 2014-10-09}}</ref> He died in poverty of lung cancer.<ref name =\"BP\">{{cite web|title=J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|url=https://kangur.uek.krakow.pl//biblioteka/retinger/B.%20Podgorski%20-%20J.H.%20Retinger%201888-1960.pdf|lang=pl|page=53|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> He was buried at [[North Sheen Cemetery]] in the presence of five British cabinet ministers as well as of his two younger daughters who were finally reconciled with him.<ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\"/>{{rp|pages=16\u201322}} According to the oration of Sir [[Edward Beddington-Behrens]], Retinger not only had special access to [[10 Downing Street]] but also to the [[White House]].<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> \n[[File:Gr\u00f3b J\u00f3zefa Hieronima Retingera.jpg|thumb|right|Retinger's grave, [[North Sheen Cemetery]], London]]\nRetinger's long time personal assistant and the editor of his posthumous memoirs, John Pomian, actually {{Interlanguage link|Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz|pl}}, was another Polish emigr\u00e9 in London, later a director of the Heim gallery in London's [[St James's]], owned by the influential Polish art historian and philanthropist, [[Andrzej Ciechanowiecki]].<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://nekrologi.wyborcza.pl/0,11,,373783,Jan-Pomiana-B%C5%82awdziewicza-kondolencje.html | title =Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz | trans-title=Obituary of Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz|journal = Wyborcza.pl |date=2015| lang = pl | access-date = 2016-10-28}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRetinger married twice. In 1912 he wed the well-born Otolia Zubrzycka (divorced 1921, died 1984), with whom he had a daughter, Malina (later Puchalska). In 1926 he wed Stella Morel (died 1933), daughter of French-born pacifist and [[Dundee]] member of Parliament [[E.D. Morel]] and Mary, n\u00e9e Richardson, with whom he had two daughters, Maria (later Fforde) and Stasia (later French). Among his grandchildren are David French, and fantasy novelist, [[Jasper Fforde]].\n\nDuring the Great War and after, Retinger appears to have fallen under the spell of several women, especially the American journalist [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]], a supposed lover of Joseph Conrad.<ref name= \"JM\">{{cite book|title=Joseph Conrad: A Biography|author= Meyers, Jeffrey|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|date= 2001|page=361|isbn=978-0-8154-11123}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=The Athens Observer|first=Donald E.|last=Wilkes|title=Jane Anderson: The Nazi Georgia Peach|url=http://digitalcommons.law.uga.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1019&context=fac_pm|date=May 18, 1995|page=5|accessdate=24 August 2013}}</ref> Retinger's own liaison with Anderson brought about the breakdown of Retinger's marriage to Otolia and drove a wedge between him and his friend Conrad.<ref name= \"JM\"/>{{rp|page=293}} However Conrad biographer, John Stape, gives an alternative version for the cooling of relations between the two men, suggesting instead that as Retinger's enthusiasms were not shared by the novelist, shortly after the war, without his charming wife by his side, Retinger's proneness to exaggeration and tactlessness made him less socially acceptable.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Several Lives of Joseph Conrad|author= Stape, John|publisher=Random House|date= 2010|pages=187\u2013188|isbn=978-1409006824}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nOver the decades since his 1960 death, the left-leaning Retinger continues to draw fascination and controversy with his political skill, his apparently selfless single-mindedness, and his lasting institutional legacy in Europe and beyond.<ref>{{cite book|author=Wisnewski, Gerhard|title=The Bilderbergers Puppet-Masters of Power?: An Investigation into Claims of Conspiracy at the Heart of Politics, Business and the Media|translator=J. Collis|trans-title=Drahtzieher der Macht (2010)|date=2014|place=West Sussex|publisher=Clairview Books|isbn=978-1-90557075-1|pages=63\u201366}}</ref> [[Adam Pragier]], a notable Polish exile and trenchant political commentator (and a secondary-school contemporary of Retinger's), has described him as \"a sort of adventurer, but in the good sense of the word\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Czas przesz\u0142y dokonany - Czasy i ludzie|author= Pragier, Adam|work=Czas przesz\u0142y dokonany, Part 1|series= volume 7 of 100-lecie Niepodleg\u0142o\u015bci - 100th anniversary of Polish independence|editors=Friszke, Andrzej and Peja\u015b, Ewa|location=Warsaw|publisher=[[Museum of Polish History]]|date= 2018|isbn=978-8-3652-4829-9|orig-year=First published by B. \u015awiderski in London 1966|page=852|trans-title=The Past Perfect - Lives and Times}}</ref> On the other hand, detractors impugn his influence due to alleged connections, with deeply secret and malign factions, for which there is so far no reliable evidence.<ref>{{cite journal|author=K\u0119der, Wojciech|title=Recenzje: Bogdan Podg\u00f3rski, J\u00f3zef Retinger prywatny polityk, Universitas, Krak\u00f3w 2013, ss. 417.\n|journal=Studia Sandomierskie 23|date= 2016|pages=303\u2013314|lang=pl|trans-title=Review of Bogdan Podg\u00f3rski, ''J\u00f3zef Retinger private politician''. Krak\u00f3w: Universitas. 2013, pages 417.|url=https://journals.indexcopernicus.com/api/file/viewByFileId/84684.pdf}}\n</ref><ref>{{Cite web|author=Cornell, Svante E|title=Erbakan, K\u0131sak\u00fcrek, and the Mainstreaming of Extremism in Turkey |publisher=[[Hudson Institute]]|date=2018 |url=https://www.hudson.org/research/14375-erbakan-k-sak-rek-and-the-mainstreaming-of-extremism-in-turkey|access-date=2020-04-03}} see fn. 19.</ref> He remains an enigma, and probably the one substantial contributor to postwar European peace who has no physical monument.<ref name = \"BP\"/>{{rp|page=60}}\n\nIn 2000 [[The Daily Telegraph]]'s [[Ambrose Evans-Pritchard]] revealed, from declassified US Government records, that:\n{{blockquote|The leaders of the European Movement \u2013 Retinger, the visionary [[Robert Schuman]] and the former Belgian prime minister [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] \u2013 were all treated as hired hands by their American sponsors. The US role was handled as a covert operation. ACUE\u2019s funding came from the [[Ford Foundation|Ford]] and [[Rockefeller Foundation]]s as well as business groups with close ties to the US government.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/1356047/Euro-federalists-financed-by-US-spy-chiefs.html|title=Euro-federalists financed by US Spy Chief|author= Ambrose Evans-Pritchard|date=18 September 2000|publisher= The Daily Telegraph|author-link=Ambrose Evans-Pritchard}}</ref>}} This revelation touching on [[Cold War]] circumstances was subsequently analysed in greater detail in 2003 by ''[[Le Figaro Magazine|Le Figaro]]'' commentator {{Interlanguage link|R\u00e9mi Kauffer|fr}}.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kauffer, R\u00e9mi|title=Quand la CIA finan\u00e7ait la construction europ\u00e9enne - Par R\u00e9mi Kauffer, Source : Historia 2003|date=12 June 2019|url=http://www.comite-valmy.org/spip.php?article516|publisher=Comit\u00e9 Valmy|lang=fr|trans-title=When the CIA financed the construction of Europe by R\u00e9mi Kauffer, source: Historia 2003|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> However, as professor Hugh Wilford shows, the initiative to win American backing for a \"United States of Europe\" came neither from [[Allen Dulles]], deputy chief, then chief of the [[CIA]], nor from Senator [[William Fulbright]], chairman of the [[American Committee on United Europe]], but from European lobbyists of disparate motivation, namely Coudenhove-Kalergi and Retinger, the latter eclipsing the former due to Retinger's close connection with Winston Churchill on European matters.<ref name=\"wilford\"/> Retinger's plan was that the [[United States]] should be integral to political and economic support for a war-damaged [[Western Europe]]. As \"head of casting\" for his project, he set about finding key Americans to collaborate with him, among them [[Charles Douglas Jackson]], [[Time Inc.|Time-Life]] publisher in the 1940s and one-time head of propaganda at the [[Dwight D. Eisenhower|Eisenhower]] White House.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Bilderberg Conspiracy: Inside the World\u2019s Most Powerful Secret Society|author=Jeffers, H. Paul|chapter= 1|publisher= Kensington Publishing Corp.|date= 2012|isbn= 978-0-8065-3595-1}}</ref>\n\nRetinger has inspired disparate opinions. He was a figure whose allegiances, like his roots, remain obscure and whose accounts of himself varied according to his audience, thus undercutting his reliability \u2013 as reflected in various [[Joseph Conrad]] biographies and numerous other sources, including the considered, annotated review, by [[Norbert W\u00f3jtowicz]] of  Poland's [[Institute of National Remembrance]], of [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt|Marek Celt]]'s 2006 posthumously published ''Z Retingerem do Warszawy i z powrotem. Raport z podziemia 1944'', [''To Warsaw with Retinger and Back. A Report from the Underground 1944''] edited by Wojciech Frazik.<ref>{{cite web|author= Norbert W\u00f3jtowicz|title=Recenzja: Marek Celt, Z Retingerem do Warszawy i z powrotem. Raport z Podziemia 1944, red. Wojciech Frazik, Wydawnictwo LTW, \u0141omianki 2006 |trans-title = Review of Marek Celt, To Warsaw with Retinger and Back. A Report from the Underground 1944, ed. Wojciech Frazik pub. LTW. \u0141omianki, 2006|url=http://www.polska1918-89.pl/pdf/marek-celt,-z-retingerem-do-warszawy-i-z-powrotem.-raport-z-podziemia-,5423.pdf|publisher=www.polska1918-89|lang=pl|access-date=2020-03-31}} The book was subsequently translated into English by Jan Chciuk-Celt and published by McFarland in 2013 as ''Parachuting into Poland, 1944: Memoir of a Secret Mission with Jozef Retinger'', {{ISBN|978-1-4766-03384}} \"Marek Celt\", the pseudonym of Tadeusz Chciuk, was the military courier who accompanied Retinger on his parachute mission to Poland in 1944. A bond of friendship developed between the two men and they collaborated again on supplying aid to Warsaw from London in 1945-6.</ref> The disparity in views on Retinger, despite the perception of some personality flaws, does not alter Retinger's mature postwar European legacy.<ref>{{cite web|title= J\u00f3zef Retinger|publisher=bilderbergmeetings.co.uk|url= http://bilderbergmeetings.co.uk/jozef-retinger/|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n== Selected works==\nBy J. H. Retinger:\n* {{cite book|date= 1908|title=Le conte fantastique dans le romantisme fran\u00e7ais|place= Gen\u00e8ve|publisher= Slatkine Reprints, 1973|trans-title=Fantastical Tales in the French Romantic Tradition|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite book|title=Histoire de la litt\u00e9rature fran\u00e7aise du romantisme \u00e0 nos jours|place= Paris|publisher=[[Bernard Grasset| B. Grasset]]|date= 1911|trans-title=The History of French Literature from Romanticism to the Present Day|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite book|title= The Poles and Prussia|place=London|date=1913|url=https://explore.library.leeds.ac.uk/special-collections-explore/334918/the_poles_and_prussia?subject=%22Polish%20question%22&resultOffset=2}} available at University of Leeds Library\n* {{cite book|title=La Pologne et l'\u00c9quilibre europ\u00e9en|place= Paris|date= 1916|trans-title=Poland and the Stability of Europe|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite book|title=Morones of Mexico; a history of the labour movement in that country|place=London|publisher= The Labour Pub. Co. Ltd.|date= 1926}}\n* {{cite book|title=Tierra mexicana; the history of land and agriculture in ancient and modern Mexico|place= London|publisher= N. Douglas|date= 1928}}\n* {{cite book|title=Polacy w cywilizacjach zagranicznych|trans-title= Poles in Foreign Civilizations|place=Warsaw|date= 1934|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite journal|title= Historja i polityka: Nowy czynnik w dyplomacji mi\u0119dzynarodowej|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie (50)|date= 4 December 1938|trans-title=History and Politics: A new factor in international diplomacy|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite journal|title= Historja i polityka: Zast\u00f3j w mi\u0119dzynarodowej dzia\u0142alno\u015bci Rosji|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie (51)|date= 11 December 1938|trans-title=History and Politics: Suspension of Russian activity in international relations|lang=pl}} \n* {{cite book|title=All about Poland: facts, figures, documents|place= London|publisher= Minerva Pub. Co.|date= 1941}}\n* {{cite book|title=Conrad and His Contemporaries |year=1942 |publisher=Roy |location=New York|orig-year=First published by Minerva, London, 1941}}\n*  {{cite book|title= The European Continent? Address given to the Royal Institute of International Affairs in London|url=https://www.cvce.eu/content/publication/2008/2/19/534c684a-8924-445a-8181-58360f939f56/publishable_en.pdf|date= 7 May 1946|place=London}}\n*  {{cite book|title=The Bilderberg Group|place= Hertfordshire, UK|date= 1959}}\n*  {{cite book|title=Under Polish eyes|place=United Kingdom|publisher= Joseph Conrad Society|date= 1975}}\n\nAbout Retinger:\n* {{cite journal|author=Poraj, Stanis\u0142aw|title= The knight among nations|journal= Tydzie\u0144 Literacki Polski Zbrojnej, 2 (24)|lang=pl|date= 19 June 1938}}\n* {{cite book|author=[[Denis de Rougemont|de Rougemont, Denis]]|date= 1961|title=A Biographical Sketch. In Tribute to a Great European|editor= Retinger, J.H.|pages=20\u201350|place= Geneva|publisher= Centre Europe\u00e9n de la Culture|lang=}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Siemaszko, Zbigniew Sebastian|date=1967|title= Retinger w Polsce 1944 r.|place=Paris|journal= Zeszyty Historyczne, 12|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|title=J\u00f3zef Retinger: Memoirs of an Eminence Grise|editor=Pomian, John|publisher= Sussex University Press/Chatto & Windus|date= 1972| isbn=0-85621-002-1|oclc=844436367}}.\n* {{cite book|author=[[Jan Nowak-Jeziora\u0144ski|Nowak, Jan]]|title= Kurier z Warszawy|place= London|publisher= Odnowa|date= 1978|lang=pl|isbn= 0-903705-37-0}}\n* {{cite book|publisher=[[Polski S\u0142ownik Biograficzny]]|title= J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|volume= XXXI|date= 1988-1989|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|title=In remembrance of Joseph Retinger 1988-1960, Initiator of the European League for Economic Cooperation|publisher= [[European League for Economic Cooperation]]|place= Brussels|date= 1996}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Grosbois, Thierry|date= 1999|title=L'action de J\u00f3zef Retinger en faveur de l'id\u00e9e europ\u00e9enne 1940-46|journal= Revue Europ\u00e9enne d'Histoire| volume= 6|issue= 34|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Kalicki, W\u0142odzimierz|date=2010|title=Gracz, kt\u00f3ry budowa\u0142 Europ\u0119|trans-title=The Player who built Europe|journal= Gazeta Wyborcza |issue=219|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|authors=\t[[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt|Marek Celt]], Jan Chciuk-Celt|title=Parachuting into Poland, 1944: Memoir of a Secret Mission with Jozef Retinger|publisher=McFarland|date= 2013|isbn=978-1-4766-03384}}\n* {{cite book|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|title= J\u00f3zef Retinger \u2013 prywatny polityk|trans-title=J\u00f3zef Retinger - a private politician|publisher= Universitas|date= 2013|lang=pl|isbn=97883-242-2351-0}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of governments in exile during World War II]]\n*[[European Movement]]\n*[[European Union]]\n*[[List of Poles#Diplomats|List of Poles]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal|author=Pragier, Adam|title=Nie by\u0142o k\u0142opotu z Polakami|trans-title=There was no Problem with the Poles|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci, Rok 10, Nr 21 (477)|lang=pl|date=1955-05-22|place=London|url=http://retropress.pl/wiadomosci/nie-bylo-klopotu-z-polakami/}}\n* {{cite book|author=Bines, Jeffrey|title=Poland's S.O.E: A British Perspective: the Story of the Polish Country Section of the Special Operations Executive 1940-1946 Including the British Military Mission Number Four to Poland 1939|publisher=Polish Underground Movement Study Trust|date= 2018|place=London|isbn=978-0-9928-03056}} \n* {{cite j