49\u201366|doi=10.5406/polishreview.60.4.0049}}\n* {{cite book|author=Wisnewski, Gerhard|title=The Bilderbergers Puppet-Masters of Power?: An Investigation into Claims of Conspiracy at the Heart of Politics, Business and the Media|translator=J. Collis|trans-title=Drahtzieher der Macht (2010)|date=2014|place=West Sussex|publisher=Clairview Books|isbn=978-1-90557075-1|pages=63\u201366}}\n* {{cite book|title=Informal Alliance: The Bilderberg Group and Transatlantic Relations during the Cold War, 1952-1968|series=  Routledge Studies in Modern History|author=Gijswijt, Thomas W.|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date= 2018|isbn=978-1-3511-8102-0}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20161027232624/http://home.teleport.com/~flyheart/retinger.htm Illustrated biography of Jozef Retinger assembled by Jan Chciuk-Celt]\n*[https://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/205254911 Polish Soviet Relations During The Second World War, photographs held by the [[Imperial War Museum]] with J\u00f3zef Retinger (extreme left) at the signing of the Sikorski-Maiski agreement at the FO on 30.07.1941]\n*[http://www.jasperfforde.com/ten_things/ten_things8.html Photograph of Retinger flanking Churchill at the Hague 1948, on Retinger's grandson's website]\n*[http://www.bilderberg.org/bildhist.htm#Memoirs Chapter 4, European Unity, from ''Memoirs of An Eminence Grise'' ed. John Pomian]\n*[http://bilderbergmeetings.co.uk/jozef-retinger/ Bilderberg website on Retinger's life in brief]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Retinger, Jozef}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Poland to Russia]]\n[[Category:Council of Europe]]\n[[Category:Members of the Steering Committee of the Bilderberg Group]]\n[[Category:Polish politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Freemasons]]\n[[Category:European integration pioneers]]\n[[Category:Geopoliticians]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Polish diplomats]]\n[[Category:Polish spies]]\n[[Category:Secret Intelligence Service personnel]]\n[[Category:Special Operations Executive personnel]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish writers]]\n[[Category:Exophonic writers]]\n[[Category:Polish essayists]]\n[[Category:Male essayists]]\n[[Category:Polish political writers]]\n[[Category:Polish people of World War II]]\n[[Category:People of World War II]]\n[[Category:History of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Rusyn descent]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGrasset(link changed to\u00c9ditions Grasset) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J%C3%B3zef_Retinger"}
{"title_page": "Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o", "text_new": "{{short description|Cultural institution in Puerto Rico founded in 1876}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name               = Puerto Rican Athenaeum<br>''Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o''\n| image              = Ateneo_Puertorrique\u00f1o_logo_1876.jpg\n| logo_caption       = Official Seal\n| map                = {{Location map| Puerto Rico\n| AlternativeMap = USA_Puerto_Rico_location_map.svg\n| width          = 225\n| float          = center\n| caption        = \n| mark           = Red_pog.svg\n| alt            = Map of Puerto Rico with mark showing location of Puerto Rican Athenaeum\n| label          = Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o\n| lat_deg        = 18   | lat_min = 27 | lat_dir = N\n| lon_deg        = 66  | lon_min = 6  | lon_dir = W\n}}\n| headquarters       = [[Puerta de Tierra]], [[Old San Juan]], San Juan, Puerto Rico\n| location           = [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n| region             = Puerto Rico\n| language           = Spanish\n| board_of_directors = Junta de Gobierno del Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o<ref name=board_of_directors>As of April 20, 2020. {{cite web |url=https://ateneopr.org/contactus.html |title=Board of Governors |access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| type               = Not-for-profit cultural institution\n| registration_id    = 352044\n| purpose            = Promote the affirmation and development of the Puerto Rican nationality, as well as engage in cultural, educational and social activities.\n| nickname           = \"El Ateneo\"<br /><small>(English: \"The Athenaeum\")</small>\n| named_after        = [[Athenaeum (ancient Rome)|Athenaeum]]\n| motto              = ''Ad Majorem Patriae Gloriam''<br /><small>(English: \"For the greater glory of our country\")</small>\n| founded            = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1876|04|30}}\n| founders           = Manuel de Elzaburu y Vizcarrondo, [[Jos\u00e9 Juli\u00e1n Acosta]], [[Alejandro Tapia y Rivera]], and Francisco de Paula Acu\u00f1a y Paniagua\n| founding_location  = [[San Juan City Hall]]\n| endowment          = $466,636.00 (2018)<ref name=endowment>As of April 11, 2019. {{cite web |url=https://prcorpfiling.f1hst.com/CorrespondenceHandler.ashx?WGUID=9bf3e51d-fd1b-4c9a-acaa-8fcabb573318&SEQ=8959315&IE=0 |title=Anual Report |publisher=[[Puerto Rico Department of State]] |access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| website            = {{URL|https://ateneopr.org/}}\n}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name                = Puerto Rican Athenaeum<br>''Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o''\n| groundbreaking_date = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1923|05|27}}\n| architect           = Francisco Rold\u00e1n Arce\n| parking             = 14<br />(Disabled: 1)\n| floor_count         = 2\n| architectural_style = Spanish Morisco\n| image               = Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o (01).jpg\n| caption             = \n}}\nThe '''Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o''' ('''Puerto Rican Athenaeum'''), is a cultural institution in [[Puerto Rico]]. Founded in April 30 1876<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite web|url=https://ateneopr.org/aboutus.html|title=Ateneo-Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o|website=ateneopr.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>, it has been called Puerto Rico's oldest cultural institution,<ref>{{cite journal|date=March 5, 2015|title=Renuncia el presidente del Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/noticias/locales/nota/renunciaelpresidentedelateneopuertorriqueno-2016199/|journal=El Nuevo Dia|language=es|accessdate=October 15, 2016}}</ref> however, it is actually its third oldest overall and second culturally, after the [[Bar Association of Puerto Rico]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://capr.org/historia/|title=Historia|website=capr.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> and the Casino of Mayag\u00fcez.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mayaguezsabeamango.com/archivos/historias-final/1300-el-casino-de-mayagueez-la-institucion-mas-antigua-en-su-clase|title=El Casino de Mayag\u00fcez, la instituci\u00f3n m\u00e1s antigua en su clase|last=Gaudier|first=Mart\u00edn|date=|website=Mayag\u00fcez Sabe a Mang\u00f3|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOne of its founders was the playwright, [[Alejandro Tapia y Rivera]].<ref name=\":03\" /> The Athenaeum was the first to give accolades and awards to artists and [[List of Puerto Rican writers|writers]] such as [[Jos\u00e9 Gautier Ben\u00edtez]], [[Jos\u00e9 de Diego]], Manuel Mar\u00eda Sama, [[Francisco Oller]], [[Manuel Fern\u00e1ndez Juncos]], [[Lola Rodr\u00edguez de Ti\u00f3]] and [[Luis Llor\u00e9ns Torres]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ramos-Perea|first=Roberto|url=http://www.80grados.net/lo-que-es-y-lo-que-vale-el-ateneo-puertorriqueno/|title=Lo que es y lo que vale el Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o|date=2011-11-18|work=80 Grados|access-date=2020-04-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Nilita Vient\u00f3s Gast\u00f3n]] became its first female president in 1946 and was the incubment until 1961.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://generales.uprrp.edu/programa-mujer-genero/conferencia-magistral-nilita-vientos-gaston/|title=Conferencia Magistral Nilita Vient\u00f3s Gast\u00f3n|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> In 1976 the Athenaeum celebrated its centennial with Eladio Rodr\u00edguez Otero at the helm as president, who gave a speech in presence of the then governor [[Rafael Hern\u00e1ndez Col\u00f3n]], [[Hiram Torres Rigual]], in representation of the [[Supreme Court of Puerto Rico]], and former governor [[Luis A. Ferr\u00e9]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rodr\u00edguez-Otero|first=Eladio|url=https://eladiorodriguezotero.com/pdf/ERO_IV_Ateneo.pdf#page=142|title=Obras Completas|publisher=D\u2019vinni|year=2008|isbn=978-0-9795080-5-9|location=San Juan, Puerto Rico|pages=128-144}}</ref> To commemorate the event, the Athenaeum also commisioned a medal to be awarded to those who represent \"the highest national values expressed through [[Culture of Puerto Rico|[Puerto Rican] culture]].\" The Centennial Medal of the Puerto Rican Athenaeum was most recently awarded to the musical salsa group [[El Gran Combo de Puerto Rico|El Gran Combo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://laprensasalsera.com/el-gran-combo-de-puerto-rico-recibe-prestigiosa-medalla-del-centenario-del-ateneo-puertorriqueno/|title=El Gran Combo de Puerto Rico recibe prestigiosa Medalla del Centenario del Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o {{!}} ..:: La Prensa Salsera ::..|language=es-ES|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nThe Athenaeum serves as a [[museum]], [[school]], [[library]], and [[Concert hall|performance hall]] for the arts in Puerto Rico. It hosts a number of contests, conferences, and exhibits each year, presenting Puerto Rican art, literature, and music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eladoquintimes.com/2016/04/16/el-ateneo-puertorriqueno-140-anos-de-la-casa-de-la-nacion-puertorriquena-por-milton-rua-de-mauret-en-la-entrada-del-casco-urbano-del-viejo-san-juan-se-encuentran-varios-edificios-importantes-a/|title=El Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o: 140 a\u00f1os de la Casa de la Naci\u00f3n Puertorrique\u00f1a|date=16 April 2016|publisher=|language=es|accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Puerto Rico 20133\">{{cite web|url=http://puertorico.com.pr/ateneo-puertorriqueno/|title=Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o|date=3 May 2013|website=Puerto Rico|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> Since 1937 the use of the spaces of the Athenaeum has been limited to activities it sponsors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511002322/http://www.puertadetierra.info/noticias/1937/ateneo_reglamento.htm|title=Reglamento del Ateneo para concesi\u00f3n de salones. 1937|date=2015-05-11|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>  Its headquarters are located in [[Puerta de Tierra, Puerto Rico|Puerta de Tierra]], adjacent to [[Old San Juan]], in a strip that also houses the \"[[Casa de Espa\u00f1a]]\", the [[Biblioteca Carnegie|Carnegie Library]], the [[Capitol of Puerto Rico|Capitol complex]] and the [[Puerto Rico Olympic Committee]] headquarters.\n\n== The Athenaeum Building<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511002322/http://www.puertadetierra.info/noticias/1937/ateneo_reglamento.htm|title=Reglamento del Ateneo para concesi\u00f3n de salones. 1937|date=2015-05-11|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> ==\nIn 1922 the [[Aguadilla, Puerto Rico|Aguadillan]] architect, Francisco Rold\u00e1n Arce was asked to draw up plans for the present building. The cornerstone was laid in 27 May 1923 in the presence of [[Jos\u00e9 Coll y Cuch\u00ed|Jos\u00e9 Coll y Cuchi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ricardoolivenc1/status/1245193883849498626|title=Colocaci\u00f3n de la primera piedra del Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o: Emilio del Toro, Jos\u00e9 M. Lago, Francisco de Paula Acu\u00f1a, Jos\u00e9 Coll y Cuch\u00ed, Manuel Calder\u00f3n, Ferdinand Cestero, Armando Miranda, Manuel Quevedo, Luis Villaronga y Ram\u00f3n Carbia. San Juan, Puerto Rico. 27 de mayo de 1923pic.twitter.com/YHfE1CiWXF|last=Olivencia|first=Ricardo|date=2020-03-31|website=@ricardoolivenc1|language=es|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> The architecture of the building, Spanish Morisco, was introduced to Puerto Rico by [[Pedro Adolfo de Castro|Pedro de Castro]], who also built some of the structures that neighbor close by. De Castro's tropical and meditarrenean conscience objected to the architecture imported from the north, giving preference to the luminosity of the Caribbean, to the visual continuity of the spaces, to the galleries and balcnies that served as a transition betnweent interior and exterior spaces, shaped by the urban enviorement, the countryside or the inner courtyards.\n\n== The Athenaeum Art Gallery ==\nThe Athenaeum's pride is its galler of art, which consists of 459 artworks.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.prfrogui.com/home/ateneo.html|title=El Ateneo-datos y fotos-Puerto Rico|website=www.prfrogui.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Among the artworks held at the Atheneum one of its most recognizable is [[Francisco Oller|Francisco Oller's]] 1890 painting \"''La Escuela del Maestro [[Rafael Cordero (educator)|Rafael Cordero]]\".''\n\n== Membership ==\nThe membership of the Athenaeum is divided between four classes: \n\n* Founders-48 inscirbed before the inaguration of the institution. \n* Of Merit-Those who gave services to the Atheneaum. \n* Of Number \n* Accidentals-Those who pay their monthly dues. \n\n== Faculty ==\nThe Puerto Rican Atheneum names members of Puerto Rico's cultural community to endowed chairs which cover a broad spectrum.\n\n=== Experimental Theatre of the Athenaeum<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ateneopr.org/teatro.html|title=C\u00e1tedra de Teatro-Ateneo Puertorrque\u00f1o|website=ateneopr.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> ===\nThe Athenaeum commenced its work with theater under the auspices of [[Alejandro Tapia y Rivera]] and took course with the contests it has held since 1911. [[Emilio S. Belaval]] founded the first professional theater groups in 1938. The Experimental Theatre of the Puerto Rican Antheneaum was founded in 1952 as the first incumbent company of the institution. As such, one of the grestest Puerto Rican playwrights of the twentieth century, [[Ren\u00e9 Marqu\u00e9s]], commences a dissemination and creative project of drama that continues to this day, totaling over 500 productions and 26 Avant-Garde Theatre Festivals.\n\nMany participants of the Festivals are members of Puerto Rico's thespian community. The Experimental Theatre Hall, which has capacity for 200, has been the premiere of many works that are now considered classical Puerto Rican drama. The most well-known of these is Ren\u00e9 Marqu\u00e9s' [[La Carreta]], which premiered in 1953 under the patronage of the Athenaeum. Other dramatists of note whose work has also premiered have been [[Manuel M\u00e9ndez Ballester]], [[Francisco Arriv\u00ed]], [[Luis Rafael S\u00e1nchez]] and [[Myrna Casas|Myrna Casa]].\n\n==== Theatre Festivals ====\nStarted in the 1970s, the Theatre Festivals of the Puerto Rican Athenaeum with the intent of showcasing new works, both Puertorrican, as well as of foreign extraction. Between 1973 and 2003 there were 36 editions of the Theatre Festival. During each edition approximately 10 productions were pesented, except in the XIX Edition, where twenty works took place, of which fifteen young authors or puertorrican authors of note, and the XX edition, which premiered 26 plays.\n\n=== Music Chair<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ateneopr.org/musica.html|title=C\u00e1tedra de M\u00fasica|website=ateneopr.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> ===\nThe Music Chair was one of the first created in the Twentieth century. It is in charge of the [[String quartet|String Quartet]] of the Atheneaum. \n\n==== Contemporary [[Music of Puerto Rico|Puertorrican Music]] Festival ====\nStarted in 2005, it has had eight editions. \n\n=== Cinema and Video Chair ===\nCreated in 1985, the Cinema and Video Chair is dedicated to the development of the production of [[List of Puerto Rican films|film in Puerto Rico]]. It also encourages the development of plans and infrastrcuture for the financing of the local cinematographic industry. \n\nTo date, it has produced two feature-length films.\n\n== The \u201cDecolonization Torch\u201d ==\nThe sculptor [[Jos\u00e9 Buscaglia Guillermety]] designed and created<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.puertorico.com/blog/the-rich-heritage-of-ateneo-puertorriqueno/|title=The Rich Heritage of Ateneo Puertorriqueno|website=PuertoRico.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> a sculpture titled \"La Antorcha de Descolonizaci\u00f3n\" (English: Decolonization Torch). Its purpose being to \"leave consgined our right and our interest in a [[Political status of Puerto Rico|non-colonial political status]].\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.primerahora.com/noticias/puerto-rico/notas/antorcha-por-la-descolonizacion/|title=Antorcha por la descolonizaci\u00f3n|website=Primera Hora|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nIt was inagurated by the then president of the Atheneaum, Eduardo Morales Coll, on the night of 24-25 July 2007 in front of the Atheneaum Building, where it will remain until the United States propitiates the opportunity<ref name=\":1\" /> for Puerto Rico to resolve its problems as a colony.<ref name=\":0\" />  Political, cultural and sports figures participated in the inagural ceremony.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe cauldron has the engraved phrase \"Fin a la Colonia\" (English: ''End to the Colony'').<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Wakes at the Atheneaum ==\nMany wakes have been held at the Atheneaum. \n\nWednsdeay, 4 March 2015, from 10:00 a.m. till 2:00 p.m. the actor [[Braulio Castillo]], The Athenaeum is custodian of the film library and documentation of the actor's career. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telemundopr.com/noticias/local/exponen-los-restos-de-braulio-castillo-en-el-ateneo-puertorriqueno/61628/|title=Exponen los restos de Braulio Castillo en el Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o|website=Telemundo Puerto Rico|language=es|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> <ref>{{Citation|title=Expondr\u00e1n a Braulio Castillo en el Ateneo|url=https://www.wapa.tv/noticias/entretenimiento/expondran-a-braulio-castillo-en-el-ateneo_20131122252789.html|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.primerahora.com/entretenimiento/cine-tv/notas/velaran-cuerpo-de-braulio-castillo-padre-en-el-ateneo/|title=Velar\u00e1n cuerpo de Braulio Castillo, padre, en el Ateneo|website=Primera Hora|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.univision.com/entretenimiento/farandula/velan-con-todos-los-honores-a-braulio-castillo-padre|title=Velan con todos los honores a Braulio Castillo, padre|last=Univision|website=Univision|language=spanish|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://prpop.org/2015/03/don-braulio-r-castillo-cintron-mision-cumplida/|title=Don Braulio Castillo: Misi\u00f3n cumplida \u2013 Fundaci\u00f3n Nacional para la Cultura Popular {{!}} San Juan, Puerto Rico|language=es|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eldiariony.com/2015/03/04/familiares-y-amigos-despiden-al-actor-braulio-castillo-en-san-juan/|title=Familiares y amigos despiden al actor Braulio Castillo en San Juan|last=Marzo 2015|first=Por: EFE {{!}} 04 de|website=El Diario NY|language=es|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eldiariony.com/2015/03/04/familiares-y-amigos-despiden-al-actor-braulio-castillo-en-san-juan/|title=Familiares y amigos despiden al actor Braulio Castillo en San Juan|last=Marzo 2015|first=Por: EFE {{!}} 04 de|website=El Diario NY|language=es|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nMarch 2017 from 1:00 p.m. oward<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elnuevodia.com/entretenimiento/cultura/nota/unaserenataenmemoriadebrunildagarciaayala-2297961/|title=Una serenata en memoria de Brunilda Garc\u00eda Ayala|date=2017-03-06|website=El Nuevo Dia|language=es-pr|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> actress and writer Brunilda Garc\u00eda. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Cheparalitici/status/838844738912440321|title=Contin\u00faa en el Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o el homenaje p\u00f3stumo a la actriz-patriota Brunilda Garc\u00eda. Esta noche un homenaje art\u00edstico es sumado.|last=Paralitici|first=Che|date=2017-03-06|website=@Cheparalitici|language=es|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/anaminsantiago1/status/838871819687964672|title=Cimarron en velorio de Brunilda Garciapic.twitter.com/JDQtpi1ROR|last=santiago|first=anamin|date=2017-03-06|website=@anaminsantiago1|language=es|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://prpop.org/2017/03/hacia-lo-alto-brunilda-garcia/|title=Hacia lo alto, Brunilda Garc\u00eda \u2013 Fundaci\u00f3n Nacional para la Cultura Popular {{!}} San Juan, Puerto Rico|language=es|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metro.pr/pr/entretenimiento/2017/03/05/muere-actriz-escritora-brunilda-garcia.html|title=Muere actriz y escritora Brunilda Garc\u00eda|last=Services|first=Inter News|website=Metro|language=es|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metro.pr/pr/entretenimiento/2017/03/05/colegio-actores-puerto-rico-llora-partida-brunilda-garcia.html|title=Colegio de Actores de Puerto Rico llora la partida de Brunilda Garc\u00eda|last=Services|first=Inter News|website=Metro|language=es|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n7 November 2019 from 10:00 till 2:00 p.m. the television astrologer [[Walter Mercado]] Governor [[Wanda V\u00e1zquez Garced]] went and told the family she had decreed a one day of mourning.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/wandavazquezg/status/1192470971019599872|title=Ofreciendo mis respetos al astr\u00f3logo y actor, Walter Mercado y su familia en el Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o. Les notifiqu\u00e9 el decreto de un d\u00eda de duelo ante su fallecimiento. Que descanse en paz.pic.twitter.com/nxFhnULF7o|last=Garced|first=Wanda V\u00e1zquez|date=2019-11-07|website=@wandavazquezg|language=es|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fortaleza.pr.gov/content/gobernadora-decreta-un-d-de-duelo-por-el-fallecimiento-de-walter-mercado|title=Gobernadora decreta un d\u00eda de duelo por el fallecimiento de Walter Mercado {{!}} La Fortaleza|website=www.fortaleza.pr.gov|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.primerahora.com/entretenimiento/farandula/notas/un-dia-de-duelo-en-el-gobierno-por-walter-mercado/|title=Un d\u00eda de duelo en el gobierno por Walter Mercado|website=Primera Hora|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.primerahora.com/entretenimiento/farandula/notas/fotos-y-videos-segundo-dia-de-actos-funebres-de-walter-mercado/|title=FOTOS Y V\u00cdDEOS: Segundo d\u00eda de actos f\u00fanebres de Walter Mercado|website=Primera Hora|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nDuring the morning of 3 January 2020 from 9:00 till midday<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ReveronWilma/status/1212817626445099010|title=Los actos f\u00fanebres de la escritora, l\u00edder cultural y patriota puertorrique\u00f1a Marisa Rosado: ma\u00f1ana desde 9 am a 12 pm en el Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o y luego de 3 a 9 pm en la funeraria Suchville en Caparra.|last=Reveron|first=Wilma Esther|date=2020-01-02|website=@ReveronWilma|language=es|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> of activist author Marisa Rosado of the [[Hostosian National Independence Movement]], famed for her biography of [[Pedro Albizu Campos|Carlos Albizu Campos]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=28226&recCount=25&recPointer=3&bibId=626959|title=LC Catalog - Item Information (Full Record)|website=catalog.loc.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> was mourned there.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://minhpuertorico.org/index.php/noticias/55-noticias/7609-movimiento-independentista-nacional-hostosiano|title=Informaci\u00f3n sobre exequias de Marisa Rosado|website=minhpuertorico.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n6 March 2020 from 1:00 p.m. till 6:00 p.m. [[Rafael Cancel Miranda]]. Maria Lourdes summoned female members of the [[Puerto Rican Independence Party|PIP]] to recieve him at the stairs infront. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/marialourdespip/status/1235735056083283968|title=A las compa\u00f1eras de \u201cLas Lolitas\u201d: Como parte de las actividades de ma\u00f1ana viernes en la despedida de don  Rafael Cancel Miranda, estamos convocadas para estar en el Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o a la 1 de la tarde para recibirlo en las escaleras.pic.twitter.com/OjEkhunnqf|last=Lourdes|first=Mar\u00eda de|date=2020-03-05|website=@marialourdespip|language=es|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.primerahora.com/noticias/gobierno-politica/notas/muchos-llegan-para-despedirse-de-rafael-cancel-miranda/|title=Muchos llegan para despedirse de Rafael Cancel Miranda|website=Primera Hora|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091024042617/http://www.puertadetierra.info/edificios/ateneo/ateneo.htm Information in Spanish, with photos]\n* [http://www.puertorico.com/blog/the-rich-heritage-of-ateneo-puertorriqueno The Rich Heritage of Ateneo Puertorriqueno]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130506143505/http://ateneopr.org/home/ Ateneo PR Archived Site]\n*[https://issuu.com/coleccionpuertorriquena/docs/estatutos_del_ateneo_puerto-rique__ Statutes of the Puerto Rican Athenaeum (1876)]\n*[https://issuu.com/coleccionpuertorriquena/docs/estatutos_y_reglamento_del_ateneo_p Statutes and Bylaws of the Puerto Rican Athenaeum (1900)]\n*[https://issuu.com/coleccionpuertorriquena/docs/estatutos_del_ateneo_puertorrique__ Statutes of the Puerto Rican Athenaeum (1909)]\n\n{{coord|18|27|51|N|66|6|31|W|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Athenaeum}}\n[[Category:Puerto Rican culture]]\n[[Category:Museums in San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Theatres in Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:History museums in Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:1876 establishments in Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Museums established in 1876]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cultural institution in Puerto Rico founded in 1876}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Puerto Rican Athenaeum<br>''Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o''\n| image               = Ateneo_Puertorrique\u00f1o_logo_1876.jpg|thumb\n| logo_caption        = Official Seal\n| map                 = {{Location map| Puerto Rico\n| AlternativeMap = USA_Puerto_Rico_location_map.svg\n| width   = 225\n| float   = center\n| caption = \n| mark = Red_pog.svg\n| alt     = Map of Puerto Rico with mark showing location of Puerto Rican Athenaeum \n| label   = Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o\n| lat_deg = 18   | lat_min = 27 | lat_dir = N\n| lon_deg = 66  | lon_min = 6  | lon_dir = W\n}}\n| headquarters        = [[Puerta de Tierra]], [[Old San Juan]], San Juan, Puerto Rico\n| location            = [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n| region              = Puerto Rico\n| language            = Spanish\n| board_of_directors  = Junta de Gobierno del Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o<ref name=board_of_directors>As of April 20, 2020. {{cite web |url=https://ateneopr.org/contactus.html |title=Board of Governors |access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| type                = Not-for-profit cultural institution\n| registration_id     = 352044\n| purpose             = Promote the affirmation and development of the Puerto Rican nationality, as well as engage in cultural, educational and social activities.\n| nickname            = \"El Ateneo\"<br /><small>(English: \"The Athenaeum\")</small>\n| named_after         = [[Athenaeum (ancient Rome)|Athenaeum]]\n| motto               = ''Ad Majorem Patriae Gloriam''<br /><small>(English: \"For the greater glory of our country\")</small>\n| founded             = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1876|04|30}}\n| founders            = Manuel de Elzaburu y Vizcarrondo, [[Jos\u00e9 Juli\u00e1n Acosta]], [[Alejandro Tapia y Rivera]], and Francisco de Paula Acu\u00f1a y Paniagua\n| founding_location   = [[San Juan City Hall]]\n| endowment           = $466,636.00 (2018)<ref name=endowment>As of April 11, 2019. {{cite web |url=https://prcorpfiling.f1hst.com/CorrespondenceHandler.ashx?WGUID=9bf3e51d-fd1b-4c9a-acaa-8fcabb573318&SEQ=8959315&IE=0 |title=Anual Report |publisher=[[Puerto Rico Department of State]] |access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| website             = {{URL|https://ateneopr.org/}}\n}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name = Puerto Rican Athenaeum<br>''Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o''\n| embed = embed=yes\n| groundbreaking_date = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1923|05|27}}\n| architect = Francisco Rold\u00e1n Arce\n| parking = 14<br /><small>(Disabled: 1)</small>\n| floor_count = 2\n| architectural_style = Spanish Morisco\n| image = [[File:Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o (01).jpg|thumb|Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o (01)]]\n}}\nThe '''Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o''' ('''Puerto Rican Athenaeum'''), is a cultural institution in [[Puerto Rico]]. Founded in April 30 1876<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite web|url=https://ateneopr.org/aboutus.html|title=Ateneo-Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o|website=ateneopr.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>, it has been called Puerto Rico's oldest cultural institution,<ref>{{cite journal|date=March 5, 2015|title=Renuncia el presidente del Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/noticias/locales/nota/renunciaelpresidentedelateneopuertorriqueno-2016199/|journal=El Nuevo Dia|language=es|accessdate=October 15, 2016}}</ref> however, it is actually its third oldest overall and second culturally, after the [[Bar Association of Puerto Rico]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://capr.org/historia/|title=Historia|website=capr.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> and the Casino of Mayag\u00fcez.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mayaguezsabeamango.com/archivos/historias-final/1300-el-casino-de-mayagueez-la-institucion-mas-antigua-en-su-clase|title=El Casino de Mayag\u00fcez, la instituci\u00f3n m\u00e1s antigua en su clase|last=Gaudier|first=Mart\u00edn|date=|website=Mayag\u00fcez Sabe a Mang\u00f3|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOne of its founders was the playwright, [[Alejandro Tapia y Rivera]].<ref name=\":03\" /> The Athenaeum was the first to give accolades and awards to artists and [[List of Puerto Rican writers|writers]] such as [[Jos\u00e9 Gautier Ben\u00edtez]], [[Jos\u00e9 de Diego]], Manuel Mar\u00eda Sama, [[Francisco Oller]], [[Manuel Fern\u00e1ndez Juncos]], [[Lola Rodr\u00edguez de Ti\u00f3]] and [[Luis Llor\u00e9ns Torres]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ramos-Perea|first=Roberto|url=http://www.80grados.net/lo-que-es-y-lo-que-vale-el-ateneo-puertorriqueno/|title=Lo que es y lo que vale el Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o|date=2011-11-18|work=80 Grados|access-date=2020-04-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Nilita Vient\u00f3s Gast\u00f3n]] became its first female president in 1946 and was the incubment until 1961.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://generales.uprrp.edu/programa-mujer-genero/conferencia-magistral-nilita-vientos-gaston/|title=Conferencia Magistral Nilita Vient\u00f3s Gast\u00f3n|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> In 1976 the Athenaeum celebrated its centennial with Eladio Rodr\u00edguez Otero at the helm as president, who gave a speech in presence of the then governor [[Rafael Hern\u00e1ndez Col\u00f3n]], [[Hiram Torres Rigual]], in representation of the [[Supreme Court of Puerto Rico]], and former governor [[Luis A. Ferr\u00e9]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rodr\u00edguez-Otero|first=Eladio|url=https://eladiorodriguezotero.com/pdf/ERO_IV_Ateneo.pdf#page=142|title=Obras Completas|publisher=D\u2019vinni|year=2008|isbn=978-0-9795080-5-9|location=San Juan, Puerto Rico|pages=128-144}}</ref> To commemorate the event, the Athenaeum also commisioned a medal to be awarded to those who represent \"the highest national values expressed through [[Culture of Puerto Rico|[Puerto Rican] culture]].\" The Centennial Medal of the Puerto Rican Athenaeum was most recently awarded to the musical salsa group [[El Gran Combo de Puerto Rico|El Gran Combo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://laprensasalsera.com/el-gran-combo-de-puerto-rico-recibe-prestigiosa-medalla-del-centenario-del-ateneo-puertorriqueno/|title=El Gran Combo de Puerto Rico recibe prestigiosa Medalla del Centenario del Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o {{!}} ..:: La Prensa Salsera ::..|language=es-ES|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nThe Athenaeum serves as a [[museum]], [[school]], [[library]], and [[Concert hall|performance hall]] for the arts in Puerto Rico. It hosts a number of contests, conferences, and exhibits each year, presenting Puerto Rican art, literature, and music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eladoquintimes.com/2016/04/16/el-ateneo-puertorriqueno-140-anos-de-la-casa-de-la-nacion-puertorriquena-por-milton-rua-de-mauret-en-la-entrada-del-casco-urbano-del-viejo-san-juan-se-encuentran-varios-edificios-importantes-a/|title=El Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o: 140 a\u00f1os de la Casa de la Naci\u00f3n Puertorrique\u00f1a|date=16 April 2016|publisher=|language=es|accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Puerto Rico 20133\">{{cite web|url=http://puertorico.com.pr/ateneo-puertorriqueno/|title=Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o|date=3 May 2013|website=Puerto Rico|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> Since 1937 the use of the spaces of the Athenaeum has been limited to activities it sponsors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511002322/http://www.puertadetierra.info/noticias/1937/ateneo_reglamento.htm|title=Reglamento del Ateneo para concesi\u00f3n de salones. 1937|date=2015-05-11|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>  Its headquarters are located in [[Puerta de Tierra, Puerto Rico|Puerta de Tierra]], adjacent to [[Old San Juan]], in a strip that also houses the \"[[Casa de Espa\u00f1a]]\", the [[Biblioteca Carnegie|Carnegie Library]], the [[Capitol of Puerto Rico|Capitol complex]] and the [[Puerto Rico Olympic Committee]] headquarters.\n\n== The Athenaeum Building<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511002322/http://www.puertadetierra.info/noticias/1937/ateneo_reglamento.htm|title=Reglamento del Ateneo para concesi\u00f3n de salones. 1937|date=2015-05-11|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> ==\nIn 1922 the [[Aguadilla, Puerto Rico|Aguadillan]] architect, Francisco Rold\u00e1n Arce was asked to draw up plans for the present building. The cornerstone was laid in 27 May 1923 in the presence of [[Jos\u00e9 Coll y Cuch\u00ed|Jos\u00e9 Coll y Cuchi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ricardoolivenc1/status/1245193883849498626|title=Colocaci\u00f3n de la primera piedra del Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o: Emilio del Toro, Jos\u00e9 M. Lago, Francisco de Paula Acu\u00f1a, Jos\u00e9 Coll y Cuch\u00ed, Manuel Calder\u00f3n, Ferdinand Cestero, Armando Miranda, Manuel Quevedo, Luis Villaronga y Ram\u00f3n Carbia. San Juan, Puerto Rico. 27 de mayo de 1923pic.twitter.com/YHfE1CiWXF|last=Olivencia|first=Ricardo|date=2020-03-31|website=@ricardoolivenc1|language=es|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> The architecture of the building, Spanish Morisco, was introduced to Puerto Rico by [[Pedro Adolfo de Castro|Pedro de Castro]], who also built some of the structures that neighbor close by. De Castro's tropical and meditarrenean conscience objected to the architecture imported from the north, giving preference to the luminosity of the Caribbean, to the visual continuity of the spaces, to the galleries and balcnies that served as a transition betnweent interior and exterior spaces, shaped by the urban enviorement, the countryside or the inner courtyards.\n\n== The Athenaeum Art Gallery ==\nThe Athenaeum's pride is its galler of art, which consists of 459 artworks.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.prfrogui.com/home/ateneo.html|title=El Ateneo-datos y fotos-Puerto Rico|website=www.prfrogui.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Among the artworks held at the Atheneum one of its most recognizable is [[Francisco Oller|Francisco Oller's]] 1890 painting \"''La Escuela del Maestro [[Rafael Cordero (educator)|Rafael Cordero]]\".''\n\n== Membership ==\nThe membership of the Athenaeum is divided between four classes: \n\n* Founders-48 inscirbed before the inaguration of the institution. \n* Of Merit-Those who gave services to the Atheneaum. \n* Of Number \n* Accidentals-Those who pay their monthly dues. \n\n== Faculty ==\nThe Puerto Rican Atheneum names members of Puerto Rico's cultural community to endowed chairs which cover a broad spectrum.\n\n=== Experimental Theatre of the Athenaeum<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ateneopr.org/teatro.html|title=C\u00e1tedra de Teatro-Ateneo Puertorrque\u00f1o|website=ateneopr.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> ===\nThe Athenaeum commenced its work with theater under the auspices of [[Alejandro Tapia y Rivera]] and took course with the contests it has held since 1911. [[Emilio S. Belaval]] founded the first professional theater groups in 1938. The Experimental Theatre of the Puerto Rican Antheneaum was founded in 1952 as the first incumbent company of the institution. As such, one of the grestest Puerto Rican playwrights of the twentieth century, [[Ren\u00e9 Marqu\u00e9s]], commences a dissemination and creative project of drama that continues to this day, totaling over 500 productions and 26 Avant-Garde Theatre Festivals.\n\nMany participants of the Festivals are members of Puerto Rico's thespian community. The Experimental Theatre Hall, which has capacity for 200, has been the premiere of many works that are now considered classical Puerto Rican drama. The most well-known of these is Ren\u00e9 Marqu\u00e9s' [[La Carreta]], which premiered in 1953 under the patronage of the Athenaeum. Other dramatists of note whose work has also premiered have been [[Manuel M\u00e9ndez Ballester]], [[Francisco Arriv\u00ed]], [[Luis Rafael S\u00e1nchez]] and [[Myrna Casas|Myrna Casa]].\n\n==== Theatre Festivals ====\nStarted in the 1970s, the Theatre Festivals of the Puerto Rican Athenaeum with the intent of showcasing new works, both Puertorrican, as well as of foreign extraction. Between 1973 and 2003 there were 36 editions of the Theatre Festival. During each edition approximately 10 productions were pesented, except in the XIX Edition, where twenty works took place, of which fifteen young authors or puertorrican authors of note, and the XX edition, which premiered 26 plays.\n\n=== Music Chair<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ateneopr.org/musica.html|title=C\u00e1tedra de M\u00fasica|website=ateneopr.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> ===\nThe Music Chair was one of the first created in the Twentieth century. It is in charge of the [[String quartet|String Quartet]] of the Atheneaum. \n\n==== Contemporary [[Music of Puerto Rico|Puertorrican Music]] Festival ====\nStarted in 2005, it has had eight editions. \n\n=== Cinema and Video Chair ===\nCreated in 1985, the Cinema and Video Chair is dedicated to the development of the production of [[List of Puerto Rican films|film in Puerto Rico]]. It also encourages the development of plans and infrastrcuture for the financing of the local cinematographic industry. \n\nTo date, it has produced two feature-length films.\n\n== The \u201cDecolonization Torch\u201d ==\nThe sculptor [[Jos\u00e9 Buscaglia Guillermety]] designed and created<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.puertorico.com/blog/the-rich-heritage-of-ateneo-puertorriqueno/|title=The Rich Heritage of Ateneo Puertorriqueno|website=PuertoRico.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> a sculpture titled \"La Antorcha de Descolonizaci\u00f3n\" (English: Decolonization Torch). Its purpose being to \"leave consgined our right and our interest in a [[Political status of Puerto Rico|non-colonial political status]].\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.primerahora.com/noticias/puerto-rico/notas/antorcha-por-la-descolonizacion/|title=Antorcha por la descolonizaci\u00f3n|website=Primera Hora|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nIt was inagurated by the then president of the Atheneaum, Eduardo Morales Coll, on the night of 24-25 July 2007 in front of the Atheneaum Building, where it will remain until the United States propitiates the opportunity<ref name=\":1\" /> for Puerto Rico to resolve its problems as a colony.<ref name=\":0\" />  Political, cultural and sports figures participated in the inagural ceremony.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe cauldron has the engraved phrase \"Fin a la Colonia\" (English: ''End to the Colony'').<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Wakes at the Atheneaum ==\nMany wakes have been held at the Atheneaum. \n\nWednsdeay, 4 March 2015, from 10:00 a.m. till 2:00 p.m. the actor [[Braulio Castillo]], The Athenaeum is custodian of the film library and documentation of the actor's career. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telemundopr.com/noticias/local/exponen-los-restos-de-braulio-castillo-en-el-ateneo-puertorriqueno/61628/|title=Exponen los restos de Braulio Castillo en el Ateneo Puertorrique\u00f1o|website=Telemundo Puerto Rico|language=es|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> <ref>{{Citation|title=Expondr\u00e1n a Braulio Castillo en el Ateneo|url=https://www.wapa.tv/noticias/entretenimiento/expondran-a-braulio-castillo-en-el-ateneo_20131122252789.html|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.primerahora.com/entretenimiento/cine-tv/notas/velaran-cuerpo-de-braulio-castillo-padre-en-el-ateneo/|title=Velar\u00e1n cuerpo de Braulio Castillo, padre, en el Ateneo|website=Primera Hora|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.univision.com/entretenimiento/farandula/velan-con-todos-los-honores-a-braulio-castillo-padre|title=Velan con todos los honores a Braulio Castillo, padre|last=Univision|website=Univision|language=spanish|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://prpop.org/2015/03/don-braulio-r-castillo-cintron-mision-cumplida/|title=Don Braulio Castillo: Misi\u00f3n cumplida \u2013 Fundaci\u00f3n Nacional para la Cultura Popular {{!}} San Juan, Puerto Rico|language=es|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eldiariony.com/2015/03/04/familiares-y-amigos-despiden-al-actor-braulio-castillo-en-san-juan/|title=Familiares y amigos despiden al actor Braulio Castillo en San Juan|last=Marzo 2015|first=Por: EFE {{!}} 04 de|website=El Diario NY|language=es|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eldiariony.com/2015/03/04/familiares-y-amigos-despiden-al-actor-braulio-castillo-en-san-juan/|title=Familiares y amigos despiden al actor Braulio Castillo en San Juan|last=Marzo 2015|first=Por: EFE {{!}} 04 de|website=El Diario NY|language=es|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nMarch 2017 from 1:00 p.m. oward<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elnuevodia.com/entretenimiento/cultura/nota/unaserenataenmemoriadebrunildagarciaayala-2297961/|title=Una serenata en memoria de Brunilda Garc\u00eda Ayala|date=2017-03-06|website=El Nuevo Dia|language=es-pr|access